<TEXT>
in his first speech after 
leaving prison nelson mandela repeated the most famous section of 
his last previous speech his statement from the dock at the 1964 
rivonia trial 
it was a striking reminder of the importance of that trial 
which resulted in life prison sentences for the core of the african 
national congress leadership 
the trial took its name from the area near johannesburg where 
mandelas anc colleagues were arrested in a police raid on a 
farmhouse used as a secret headquarters for the guerrilla movement 
mandela already jailed for two years for his covert activities 
and 10 other men went on trial charged with sabotage and 
conspiring to overthrow the government they faced possible 
execution if convicted 
there was a very real fear of the death penalty arthur 
chaskalson one of the defense attorneys said in an interview 
not until the last day were we sure it wouldnt be imposed 
several of the defendants including mandela decided not to 
contest the sabotage charges they contended the ancs use of 
violence was a necessary last resort after the government rejected 
nonviolent protest campaigns 
despite these admissions the state summoned a parade of 
witnesses to bolster its case including guerrillasturnedinfomers 
identifed as mr x and mr y 
most witnesses lied shamelessly purposefully and apparently 
to order wrote joel joffe another defense lawyer in an 
unpublished account of the trial he said most of the witnesses 
were held for long periods in solitary confinement and subjected to 
duress 
presiding in the highceilinged main chamber of pretoria supreme 
court was justice quartus de wet described by joffe as 
politically independent but arrogant prejudiced tempermental 
he was unquestionably sensitive to the needs of the white 
society which he believed in and upheld and also of the 
government he acted out their role i think unconsciously 
joffe wrote 
joffe later moved to britain where he became a businessman and 
a trustee of oxfam a private relief agency chaskalson and george 
bizos another member of the defense team are among south africas 
most prominent civil rights lawyers 
the head of their team bram fischer was arrested in september 
1964 five months after the trial ended on charges of membership 
in the outlawed communist party he went underground while on bail 
was caught in november 1965 and sentenced to life imprisonment 
stricken with cancer he was allowed to move to a brothers home 
under house arrest and died soon afterwards in may 1975 
chaskalson said prison authorities took fischers ashes after he 
was cremated and never returned them to relatives 
the prosecuter was percy yutar described by joffe as fond of 
bogus hysteria and fake dramatics 
yutar is still a practicing lawyer but he refused to comment on 
the trial or mandelas release 
im not a politician im a legal man yutar said i dont 
discuss cases i have prosecuted 
during the trial yutar scoffed at the ancs assertion that it 
represented the wishes of the black majority 
the deceit of the accused is amazing they took it on 
themselves to tell the world that the africans in south africa are 
suppressed oppressed and depressed yutar said it is a great 
pity that the rank and file of the bantu blacks in the country 
who are peaceful lawabiding faithful and loyal should have been 
duped by false promises 
on april 20 1964 mandela entered the dock to explain why the 
anc took up arms in pursuit of freedom on sunday before tens of 
thousands of supporters in cape town mandela ended the first 
speech of his newfound freedom with the same words he used to 
conclude in pretoria 
during my lifetime i have dedicated myself to this struggle 
of the african people i have fought against white domination and i 
have fought against black domination he said 
i have cherished the ideal of a democratic and free society in 
which all persons live together in harmony and with equal 
opportunities it is an ideal which i hope to live for and achieve 
but my lord if needs be an ideal for which i am prepared to 
die 
during the fivehour statement recalled joffe the silence 
became more and more profound until it seemed that no one in the 
court dared move or breathe 
on june 12 1964 mandela and seven codefendants were sentenced 
by de wet to life in prison he said sparing them from the gallows 
was the only leniency he could show 
the defense lawyers who had become close friends with the 
accused felt both sadness and satisfaction 
wed done all we could said chaskalson these were the 
leaders of the apartheid resistance they conducted themselves with 
tremendous dignity they stated their cases so well about why 
they went into revolt against the state 
the only white man among those convicted dennis goldberg was 
freed in 1985 after he agreed to renounce violence the others 
except for mandela were freed unconditionally last october 
de wet is dead as are prime minister hendrik verwoerd and 
justice minister bj voster who oversaw the police attempt to 
smash the anc all the convicted defendants are alive the oldest 
being 80yearold govan mbeki 
could it be said that in some way the defendants won the case 
chaskalson was asked 
they certainly didnt lose he replied they had the moral 
high ground 
</TEXT>
