<TEXT>
the fall of hardline communist 
governments across eastern europe will deprive the plo and other 
arab groups of weapons and training 
until recently romania czechoslovakia east germany and poland 
provided varying degrees of material and political support to the 
plo and other groups the aid has now been halted or reduced 
these countries provided training weapons served as host 
facilities for terrorist organizations and sometimes provided 
sabotage materials said mark heller an analyst at tel aviv 
universitys jaffee center for strategic studies in israel 
i wouldnt be surprised if that activity stopped completely 
he added 
poland under the new government of premier tadeusz mazowiecki 
last year withdrew a small stipend it gave to the plos diplomatic 
mission in warsaw 
czechoslovakia used to export 540 million worth of arms a year 
some of it to the middle east but will halt all weapons exports 
when present agreements expire foreign minister jiri dienstbier 
says 
polish officials say warsaw intends to treat every arab country 
equally and that ideology has been eliminated as a factor in polish 
foreign relations 
krzysztof plominski the foreign ministrys deputy department 
director for arab and african affairs last month said poland 
opposes any form of terrorism 
us government sources reported in early 1988 that the 
terrorist abu nidal had used a warsaw trading office as a front for 
his organization the office was closed apparently at request of 
the polish government 
czechoslovak and romanian officials deny any aid to arab 
radicals since their revolutions 
yes there was military and training support to what you can 
call libyan terrorists but all of that has been suspended today 
a czechoslovak foreign ministry official told the associated press 
he spoke on condition his name not be used 
czechoslovak officials said training camps for hundreds of 
libyans and other arab radicals existed in at least one interior 
ministry school near kladno 20 miles west of prague they said it 
is now closed 
according to the israeli government press office east germany 
also provided training to plo guerrillas some of it was at the 
friedrich engels academy in dresden 
in addition to helping radicals fight czechoslovakia and other 
countries often supplied material help to mideast and north african 
countries 
at least 1 billion worth of czechoslovak machinery and 
construction projects were provided to arab countries according to 
official figures in prague 
romania which from the late 1970s trained hundreds of plo 
guerrillas at bases in the black sea port of constanta the 
southern town of calarasi and near bucharest said in january it 
had abrogated agreements concluded by toppled communist dictator 
nicolae ceausescu 
the foreign ministry said without further detail it discovered 
secret agreements that violated international law 
romanias former counterintelligence chief gen ion pacepa 
who defected to the united states in 1978 said in his book red 
horizons that bucharest gave the plo arms and hundreds of forged 
passports 
romania east germany and czechoslovakia all maintained cordial 
relations with plo leader yasser arafat and regularly hosted him as 
a guest of state in 1988 the plo offices in those countries were 
elevated to the status of embassies 
as an indication of how things are changing czechoslovakia 
resumed diplomatic relations with israel last week and east germany 
is considering reparations to jews who suffered in the holocaust of 
world war ii 
west german officials suspect the former east german leadership 
allowed arab terrorists to cross into west berlin 
in april 1986 when two us soldiers and a turkish woman were 
killed and 230 people injured in the bombing of a west berlin 
discotheque west german and us officials said they believed the 
attack was planned and executed by the libyan embassy in east 
berlin 
other terrorists acts carried out from east berlin by arabs 
included the bombing of the german arab friendship society in west 
berlins kreuzberg district in march 1986 believed to have been 
organized by a syrian 
</TEXT>
