<TEXT>
seated in a johannesburg television studio a few 
feet from an african national congress leader foreign minister pik 
botha of south africa described followers of the black guerrilla 
movement as my friends 
the ancs ahmed kathrada released a year ago after 26 years in 
jail said nothing really had changed but that he didnt doubt the 
sincerity or integrity of the white government leaders 
his face lined and somber jeff masomola of the smaller 
militant black nationalist pan african congress dismissed 
negotiations as futile 
only immediate universal suffrage for the 51 black majority he 
said will result in the taking over of this country by the 
people who own it 
veteran white liberal politician helen suzman chided botha for 
making the sort of speeches i made 30 years ago 
all were guests on the british broadcasting corps panorama 
current affairs program beamed live from johannesburg in what the 
network said was the first such appearance by south african leaders 
from across almost the entire political spectrum 
only the farright white opposition conservative party refused 
to come to the studio because its followers object to sitting in a 
room with anc members 
conservative party spokesman koos van der merwe made his 
contribution in a separate recording he nelson mandela came 
out of that jail on sunday without having given in one inch of 
his demands said van der merwe they are not interested in 
peace or democracy they want complete capitulation of the white 
people 
no one raised their voices or interrupted throughout monday 
nights nearly onehour program 
apart from two giant drawings of anc leader nelson mandela in 
the background the atmosphere resembled that of a leisurely late 
night talk show about the modern novel 
in the studio audience several whites expressed unease or 
resentment about the insistence by mandela released on sunday 
after 27 years in jail that the armed struggle should continue 
some of the blacks wondered why after decades of apartheid blacks 
were now supposed to help allay white fears 
but a black businessman suggested blacks and whites should each 
imagine how it felt to be the other at this momentous time in their 
countrys history 
a white student seated alongside a young black woman with the 
anc colors pinned on her school uniform said he was confident of a 
future where race no longer mattered 
chief mangosotho buthelezi leader of south africas largest 
tribe and its inkhata movement was equally confident that once 
round a negotiating table south africans would find a way 
blacks and whites in this country have become 
interdependent said buthelezi who rejects anc violence but 
refuses to take independece for his fragmented kwazulu homeland 
under apartheids now abandoned grand plan of giving the white 
minority permanent control 
challenged by van der merwe from offstage to say whether the 
government was prepared to yield to anc demands of universal 
suffrage in a unitary state botha looked weary 
my government has insisted that whatever constitution is 
agreed upon must have majority support said botha how we are 
going to do it will be for the various parties to decide 
he paused and added with all respect to my friends in the 
anc if they think for one moment that some of their policies are 
going to be accepted by a majority of south africans including 
black south africans i say to them they are going to be in for a 
surprise 
</TEXT>
