<TEXT>
waves of grimy crude oil spilled 
by a tanker invaded a twomile stretch of southern california beach 
monday near a refuge for endangered pelicans and other birds 
authorities closed about 10 miles of popular surfing and 
sunbathing beaches to the public for at least three weeks because 
of the health threat posed by fumes from the oil 
cleanup crews dispatched to the fouled bolsa chica state beach 
discovered what authorities called the most serious beach pollution 
since the spill of an estimated 400000 gallons wednesday the 
tanker american trader apparently punctured itself twice on its own 
anchor as it maneuvered near a submerged pipeline about two miles 
offshore 
we got hit with more oil overnight than we have in this whole 
process said tony kozlowski spokesman for cleanup coordinator 
british petroleum co plc which chartered the tanker american 
trader 
it was an unbelievable sight huntington beach mayor tom 
mays said after a helicopter tour we got hit pretty bad last 
night and its continuing today 
black waves glistening in the sun crashed to shore despite the 
efforts of a flotilla of boats working to trap the encroaching goo 
with containment booms 
the oily onslaught is near the inland bolsa chica wetlands an 
ecological reserve that is home to the endangered california brown 
pelican as well as a temporary home to thousands of migratory birds 
and much marine life 
at bolsa chica 20 miles south of downtown los angeles the 
slick ran along two miles of beach about 30 feet wide and 2 inches 
deep 
smaller ribbons of oil 4 feet wide were reported near the 
huntington beach pier about 5 miles to the south the coast guard 
said 
cleanup crews worked along a 20mile stretch of beach from bolsa 
chica south to laguna beach 
the cleanup at bolsa chica was suspended briefly when workers 
began complaining of headaches and nausea from the oily fumes but 
by midday more than 400 cleanup workers were on the beach 
kozlowski said 
there is no oil in the estuary said patrick moore of the 
state department of fish and game but birds are leaving the 
wetlands and going to the ocean and bringing the oil back to the 
estuary 
seventyone dead birds grebes gulls loons and pelicans 
have been found in the area and another 222 oilsoaked birds were 
rescued alive and taken to a treatment center moore said 
on monday evening the 811foot american tanker dropped anchor 
just inside the long beach harbor breakwater after receiving coast 
guard permission to do so the move had been delayed until the ship 
was declared clean enough to enter the harbor 
scuba divers applied temporary patches to two holes in the 
punctured hull sunday and authorities said the vessel passed 
watertight integrity tests 
onethird of the estimated 400000 gallons of alaskan crude 
still menaced the coast the coast guard said skimmers picked up 
23 percent of the spill and 43 percent evaporated or naturally 
dissipated 
city and state beaches from anaheim bay south through in 
huntington beach about 10 miles in all were closed for an 
indefinite period with a threeweek minimum authorities cited the 
danger of fumes from the oil 
it is of vital importance to keep people off the beaches the 
contaminated birds are frightened by the crowds on the beach and 
will not come ashore where they can be safely rescued said 
biologist esther burkett of fish and game 
us sen alan cranston dcalif viewed the beaches from a 
helicopter then criticized president bush for telling a news 
conference monday that the spill shouldnt be used to bolster 
arguments against offshore oil drilling bush said a tanker 
accident wasnt an indictment of drilling platform safety 
the president should read the environmental impact statements 
by his own department of the interior which point out that the 
more drilling platforms that you have the more tankers you will 
need said cranston 
on the beach politicians environmentalists and celebrities 
gathered to demand legislation at the federal and state levels 
requiring double hulls for tankers and other safeguards 
it makes no difference what the damn cost is actor james 
garner said of the expense of doublehulled tankers what matters 
is the environment the money doesnt mean anything the 
environment does 
congress is considering laws requiring doublehulled tankers on 
the state level california attorney general john van de kamp 
endorsed an initiative calling for a cleanup superfund 
