<TEXT>
president bush says he will await the expected 
visit of south african president f w de klerk before deciding 
whether to respond to the release of nelson mandela by improving 
relations with that country 
bush is barred by law from lifting us sanctions against south 
africa until specific reforms are adopted and there is strong 
support in congress for keeping the sanctions in place as a lever 
to encourage additional dismantling of white supremacist rule 
the sanctions impose severe restrictions on american investment 
in south africa and purchases of the countrys exports the 
congressional black caucus issued a statement monday saying any 
talk of lifting the sanctions is premature 
but there are other overtures the administration could make 
toward south africa in recognition of de klerks fresh approach 
toward the countrys black majority 
the united states could make some gestures to ease south 
africas international isolation by dispatching a highlevel 
emissary to pretoria or by engaging in efforts to ease united 
nations restrictions on dealing with that country 
although bush seemed in no hurry to act on any options there 
was little doubt mandelas release and other gestures improved the 
atmosphere considerably between washington and pretoria 
bush alluded to the warming on monday when he called mandelas 
release after 27 years in prison another important sign that 
south africa may soon begin negotiating a democratic nonracial 
society and at last be on the way to ending apartheid once and for 
all 
the state department said it was heartened by the moderate tone 
of mandelas remarks since his release on sunday 
we found noteworthy his expression of hope that a climate 
conducive to a negotiated settlement would be created soon so that 
there may no longer be the need for armed struggle it said 
official contacts between the two countries dropped off sharply 
after the sanctions were imposed by congress in 1986 over 
thenpresident reagans veto 
now de klerk is preparing to become the first south african 
president to visit the united states the administration issued 
separate invitations to de klerk and mandela to visit washington 
but no dates have been set 
bush told a news conference monday he wants to discuss the 
sanctions issue with both de klerk and mandela and said the two 
south africans also should negotiate 
and then out of that i think well have a much more realistic 
picture of what the united states might do in the future he said 
bush added that a white house visit by de klerk would be a 
major step in ussouth african relations but that more 
substantive action would not be appropriate until afterward 
bush said he finds some of the sanctions counterproductive and 
played down the suggestion that they had a key role in inducing 
south africa to signal moves toward a more equitable political 
system 
whats really changed is the mindset of the south african 
leadership bush said i think that we ought to give mr de 
klerk certain credit for being able to look much more realistically 
about political change and hopefully more favorably about a 
society that eventually eliminates this racism that is equated with 
apartheid 
as for the us sanctions the comprehensive antiapartheid act 
stipulated that before they could be lifted south africa had to 
free all political prisoners and meet at least three of four other 
conditions 
de klerk already has met one of the conditions by legalizing the 
african national congress and other antiapartheid groups 
but senate democratic leader george mitchell of maine said 
the essence of these conditions is the dismantling of the south 
african laws which are the foundation of their system of racial 
segregation 
no fundamental change has been made in that direction yet and 
such change must occur before we can consider lifting sanctions 
mitchell said in a statement 
other conditions include release of other political prisoners 
repeal of the state of emergency and freeing of all those detained 
under it repeal of laws which restrict where nonwhites can live 
and work and government agreement to enter goodfaith negotiations 
with representatives of the black majority 
