<TEXT>
banks with growing portfolios of sour real 
estate loans need to do a better job a top federal regulator says 
over the last year examination activity has revealed a 
significant number of fundamental deficiencies and negative trends 
in national bank real estate lending which require immediate 
attention comptroller of the currency robert l clarke said in a 
strongly worded memorandum released monday 
the memo to board members and chief executive officers at 4200 
nationally charted banks singled out three areas for criticism 
first basic lending principles have been ignored or 
compromised to increase volume and achieve higher levels of 
interest and fee income clarke said in particular banks are 
not requiring borrowers to invest enough of their own money in real 
estate projects 
second too many banks have failed to obtain accurate 
independent and timely appraisals of the real estate projects to 
which they are lending 
and third some banks are engaging in practices that make it 
difficult to determine when a real estate project is going bad 
those include inflating the loan amount so borrowers can cover the 
interest payments in the early years of the loan and operating with 
incomplete or nonexistent foreclosure policies 
clarkes warning follows earlier reports of a big increase in 
real estate problems in new england and arizona on top of existing 
problems in the oilproducing states of texas oklahoma and 
louisiana 
the level of sour real estate loans at national banks in new 
england hit 2 billion at the end of september representing 6 
percent of their real estate portfolio quadruple the default rate 
of two years ago 
in arizona national banks listed 825 million in bad real 
estate loans 20 percent of the total 
bank of new england corp the regions secondlargest bank 
holding company alone reported a 105 billion loss in 1989 
raising questions among analysts about whether it can survive 
bank management should initiate corrective action promptly 
clarke said examiners have been and will continue to be 
aggressive and have been instructed to recommend formal 
enforcement actions as appropriate 
the gettough policy of his examiners has prompted complaints 
from builders and others in new england that reliable and solvent 
borrowers were being denied credit 
clarke said nothing in the memo is intended to discourage 
sound real estate lending and that the vast majority of 
national banks have not deviated from traditional high lending 
standards 
</TEXT>
