<TEXT>
democratic gubernatorial candidate john r silber 
sparked protests from jewish organizations after saying he 
encountered racism among jews when he once considered converting 
in an article in the boston sunday globe silber who is on 
leave as president of boston university said he considered 
converting to judaism in 1948 but decided against it because of 
their treatment of converts 
i thought about it and then found out that the racism of jews 
is quite phenomenal silber told the newspaper last week 
if you are goyim considering becoming a jew you are going to 
be secondclass in that synagogue and i didnt have any interest 
at all in moving into that congregation as a secondclass citizen 
in a statement monday silber attempted to explain his comments 
and said i have never suggested that judaism is racist 
but jewish leaders decried silbers comments 
what may have been true of his own experience in 1948 with a 
certain number of jews in a particular congregation can hardly be 
accepted as the basis for a generalization said leonard zakim 
executive director of the new england chapter of the 
antidefamation league of bnai brith 
however zakim conceded that while silbers words might have 
been illchosen the comments do not diminish the candidates work 
on behalf of the jewish people 
i dont think it changes the fact of his friendship toward the 
jewish community and israel zakim said 
joel reck president of the jewish community relations council 
of greater boston said silber is and has always been close to 
and a friend and supporter of jews judaism and israel 
silber who after 1948 discovered his father was jewish was 
deterred from joining a synagogue by the reluctance of members of 
that congregation to accept him because his mother was not 
jewish his statement said monday 
nothing in that experience diminished my deep respect for 
judaism and my concern affection and support for the jewish people 
and for israel a concern that has been demonstrated with 
consistency throughout my adult life the statement said 
but state rep david b cohen president of the new england 
region of the american jewish congress protested silbers comments 
any time anyone characterizes members of an ethnic or 
religious group with a broadbrush generality he is engaging in 
just that type of stereotyping and prejudice that we are trying to 
remove from the american political scene i am astonished 
disturbed and disappointed that the term racism was used in this 
context cohen said 
lawrence d lowenthal executive director of the local american 
jewish committee said silbers remarks about jews are simply 
blatant insults to the jewish community 
</TEXT>
