<TEXT>
thousands of washington teachers are 
pressing for higher salaries with a oneday walkout today while 
the governor expressed sympathy but rejected a pay boost this 
winter 
about 200000 students faced a winters day off with the planned 
walkout by by 13000 teachers in 35 of the states 296 school 
districts eight thousand other teachers pledged to attend 
afterhour rallies and marches 
a similar stalemate is developing in west virgina where 
thousands of teachers have said they would leave their classrooms 
thursday to protest low wages and education funding despite the 
governors stand the state has no money for them 
in washington state seattles 43000 students were among those 
facing a day off the protest was mostly confined to western 
washington but teachers everywhere were angry over gov booth 
gardners decision to ignore the organizations request for 
immediate 10 percent pay increases union officials said monday 
we want the public to understand were reaching a crisis point 
in washington said teresa moore spokeswoman for the 
49000member washington education association 
but a group called citizens united for better education 
denounced the walkouts 
i dont think it sets a good example for a third grader when 
their teacher is standing on the street corner chanting hell no 
we want more said fred brown president of the 
woodinvillebased group 
the legislature approved a twostep pay boost of 10 percent last 
year the union wants another 10 percent a retroactive 6 percent 
for this school year and 4 percent in the fall 
such an increase would cost about 225 million which union 
officials said could be financed by a 611 million state budget 
surplus 
gardner a democrat who has called himself the education 
governor told a rally of about 250 school board members and 
school administrators monday that he is committed to developing a 
worldclass education system 
but he said the state budget surplus is a onetime phenomenon 
and nothing on which to base continuing salary increases 
gardner said he wants to keep one third of the windfall in 
reserve spend one third on childrens programs such as school 
improvements and hiring more child protective services workers and 
use the rest to cover other needs such as as cost increases in 
social programs and general government 
but the union said teacher salaries should be a priority 
salaries have dropped from fourth in the nation a few years 
ago to 21st today moore said that has an impact on national 
competitiveness the ability to keep good teachers and also an 
impact on how we can attract new people into the profession 
the average teacher is being paid about 33100 plus 2100 in 
supplemental pay for extra chores acording to the governors 
office of financial management starting pay is about 18000 
in west virginia at least 2400 union teachers in five counties 
had voted by monday night to walk out thursday for a rally at the 
capitol union teachers in nine other counties also voted to walk 
out but their numbers were not known 
the momentum is growing said west virginia education 
association vice president jennie shaffer 
west virginias 22000 teachers earn an average of 21904 a 
year which ranks 48th nationally according to union leaders gov 
gaston caperton has not included a pay raise in his 199091 budget 
the governor has said over and over and over again that 
there is no money for teacher raises in 199091 spokesman gc 
morse said monday night theres gotta be a point where people 
realize were not making this up 
but mary carden president of the boone county education 
association said theres a myth that the state is broke and 
were not buying into it weve had two governors who said they 
wanted to help education and they havent done it 
