the sevenweek warm streak in the west and plains shattered 
today as arctic air drove temperatures far below the recordsetting 
readings set earlier this week the southern plains southeast and 
gulf states however looked for the heat to continue 
temperatures along the front range of the northern rockies were 
predicted to fall by as much as 50 degrees and tumble to below zero 
today in the upper midwest 
alaska enjoyed a warming trend today as an 18day cold snap 
ended with cloudiness and higher temperatures spreading across the 
state temperatures within the arctic circle were expected to rise 
above zero for the first time since the third week of january 
todays forecast called for cold moist winds to dump snow from 
montana to northeastern colorado and parts of nebraska mountain 
snow was predicted today for parts of california washington utah 
and idaho 
the arctic front cooled avalanche threats in washingtons 
cascades and flood threats on the chehalis river 
