<TEXT>
soviet soldiers and armored vehicles controlled 
the center of tadzhikistans capital today but rioting that claimed 
the lives of seven people and injured scores was spreading to the 
suburbs a journalist reported 
rioting broke out in the central asian republics capital of 
dushanbe on monday after rumors spread that armenian refugees from 
ethnic violence in the caucasus were being given preference for new 
housing at the expense of natives 
the rioters smashed windows and set fire to the ground floor of 
the republics communist party headquarters and attacked stores and 
passersby said anatoly larenov a correspondent for the national 
newspaper vozdushny transport 
seven people were killed and 79 hospitalized with injuries he 
said 
musafar madzhidov correspondent for official radio and 
television in dushanbe said rioting broke out after two rallies in 
a 24hour period prompted by the rumors of preferential housing 
members of the crowd shouted down with the armenians he 
said 
the soviet news agency tass reported monday night that a state 
of emergency was declared in the city to quell mass disorders and 
pogroms and acts of arson and looting it said a 10 pm to 6 
am curfew was imposed 
it was the latest violent flareup in ethnic unrest that has 
spread throughout the soviet unions southern rim in recent months 
as moscow loosens control and allows nationalist mass movements to 
gain strength and challenge communist authorities 
larenov said in a telephone interview that the center of 
dushanbe was quiet today after the curfew ended for the night 
tanks and soldiers were stationed in front of the party 
headquarters banks and other institutions and the center of the 
city was under military control 
but he said trouble was spreading to the suburbs of dushanbe a 
city of more than 500000 people 
larenov said officials had evacuated armenian families before 
the trouble started monday and that most of the anger was directed 
at russianspeaking people a list of those killed did not appear 
to include any armenian names 
armenians a predominantly christian people have been involved 
for the last two years in bloody dispute with predominantly moslem 
azerbaijanis over control of the nagornokarabakh region of 
azerbaijan 
more than 200 people have been killed in the southern caucasus 
republics of armenia and azerbaijan since jan 13 president 
mikhail s gorbachev sent thousands of soldiers into the area to 
end a nationalist revolt in the azerbaijani capital of baku and end 
attacks on armenians 
until monday there had been no reports that the trouble had 
spread to the predominantly moslem republics of soviet central asia 
such as tadzhikistan 
madzhidov said that tadzhikistans communist party leader 
kakhar makhkamov appeared before a crowd that gathered sunday 
outside party headquarters in dushanbe and asked for 24 hours to 
investigate rumors armenian refugees had been guaranteed housing in 
new suburbs while tadzhiks were kept waiting 
another crowd gathered on monday but ignored his report that 
all but one armenian refugee already had left dushanbe he said by 
telephone 
they pelted the party headquarters with stones breaking all the 
windows and then went on a rampage through shops located nearby 
he said 
police fired in the air to disperse the crowd but the rioting 
continued until armored vehicles brought soldiers into the city 
center madzhidov said 
families in tadzhikistan a small mountainous republic bordering 
china and afghanistan traditionally are large and there is a 
critical shortage of housing some of the mainly moslem tadzhiks 
also remain homeless after an earthquake in the republic in january 
1989 that killed scores of people 
