<TEXT>
a decade after embarking on a 
comprehensive study of acid rain scientists say theres no quick 
fix for the pollution that can despoil mountain lakes and kill 
towering trees 
but scientists from around the word who gathered here to review 
the research were told monday their work has brought the problem 
into better focus 
about 700 scientists from 35 nations are meeting this week at a 
conference sponsored by the national acid precipitation assessment 
program 
the agency was established a decade ago by congress and has 
spent 500 million investigating the problem 
at that time some people wanted to declare a national emergency 
because of acid rain said john knauss undersecretary of commerce 
for oceans and atmosphere others wanted to do nothing 
the former group those who feared the worst was convinced 
that a 10year research program was simply an excuse for postponing 
immediate action he said the latter was convinced that 
spending so much on what they saw as a nonproblem was a waste of 
precious research dollars 
today there are few left who feel we need to declare a 
national emergency just as there are few who consider acid 
deposition a nonproblem he said 
acid rain is a combination of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide 
that mixes in the atmosphere and can fall as rain snow fog and 
dust particles it can make lakes and streams acidic and can kill 
trees 
the assessment program has compiled 28 reports comprising about 
15000 pages on the causes and extent of acid rain the documents 
include no recommendations and scientists were told monday there is 
no simple answer 
the full story is seldom if ever known about the complex 
issues of environmental science said william rosenberg an 
assistant administrator for the environmental protection agency 
scientific investigation must continue including an 
evaluation of the control program put in place in the meantime we 
must take prudent actions to protect our health and our 
environment 
