close associates said tuesday the black leader had wanted to go 
straight from prison sunday to the small house on a corner built 
when the orlando section of soweto was being established in the 
early 1940s mandela worked for the municipal government then 
he and his first wife evelyn moved into the house when it was 
new and their four children spent their childhoods in it 
they were divorced in 1957 and mandela later brought his new 
wife winnie to the house an outbuilding in the yard contains 
several bedrooms where winnie mandelas notorious bodyguard stayed 
until it was disbanded last year 
the house was nearly gutted in july 1988 when boys from a nearby 
high school set it afire during a battle with members of the 
bodyguard the damage has been repaired and mandela sent orders 
from prison that no one was to be charged or prosecuted for the 
arson 
antiapartheid groups denounced mrs mandela last year for 
allowing what they called a reign of terror by her bodyguards 
nine members of the group known as the mandela united soccer 
club are charged in the death of a young activist who allegedly 
was one of four youths kidnapped and beaten at the mandela home in 
december 1988 
by the time of the fire mrs mandela already had bought a 
larger ranchstyle house in diepkloof another part of the 
township where she spent at least half her time she did not 
return to the orlando house after it was burned 
when one of mandelas african national congress colleagues 
wilton mkwayi was freed from life prison in october he occupied 
the old house temporarily on tuesday mkwayi asked the people 
outside to disperse after mandela arrived for a rest but they 
simply stood silently watching 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

