<TEXT>
astronomy will experience a true golden 
age of largetelescope construction in this decade astronomers 
and astronomical engineers say 
speakers at the society of photooptical instrumentation 
engineers international symposium heard monday about nine major 
projects in various stages of construction or planning 
the projects all intended to be operating before the end of the 
century range from a 35meter or 138inch telescope on kitt 
peak southwest of tucson to the european southern observatorys 
array of four 8meter or 316inch instruments called the very 
large telescope with the four telescopes working together the vlt 
could be the equivalent of a single 16meter or 633inch scope 
telescope designs and materials are evolving so quickly that one 
of the projects is the rebuilding of the multiple mirror telescope 
on mount hopkins south of tucson its only been operating about 10 
years and is presently the third largest in the world but the new 
telescopes will outshine it if it isnt given a bigger mirror 
the 90s will be the decade of a true golden age of 
construction of large telescopes said patrick osmer project 
scientist for the national optical astronomy observatories twin 
8meter telescopes project to be built in hawaii and chile 
basically the need for big telescopes is to get more light 
said retired noao official larry d barr detectors are 
approaching almost theoretically perfect efficiency so how do you 
detect more faint objects the answer is you build bigger 
telescopes 
also in the works are 
the university of californias keck observatory whose mirrow 
will be made up of 36 computercontrolled segments and will be 
equivalent to a 10meter or 396inch mirror nearing completion on 
hawaiis mauna kea 
the united kingdoms large telescope project also an 8meter 
telescope to be built in partnership with spain and germany in the 
canary islands or with the united states and canada on mauna kea 
the 43 million magellan 8meter telescope project involving 
the carnegie institute johns hopkins university and the university 
of arizona at las campanas chile 
the japanese national large telescope a 75meter instrument 
to stand next to the keck 
the 60 million columbus telescope project two sidebyside 
8meter telescopes resembling binoculars to be built on mount 
graham in southeastern arizona by italys arcetri observatory the 
university of arizona and ohio state university 
peter strittmatter director of the university of arizonas 
steward observatory said the latter project informally called the 
twin shooter will have the equivalent viewing power of a 
telescope 113 meters or 447 inches in diameter and twice its 
image sharpness 
the multiple mirror telescope whose six mirrors produce one 
image equivalent to that of a telescope 45 meters or 178 inches in 
diameter will be converted to a single 65meter or 257inch 
mirror to keep it competitive with the big new telescopes at a 
cost of about 155 million said director fred chaffee 
the price is very low compared to the 45 million to 50 
million for building an equivalent telescope from scratch he told 
more than 200 astronomers the mmt cost 12 million when it was 
dedicated in may 1979 
while that observatory is giving up its multiple mirrors the 
keck whose cost has been estimated at at least 90 million is 
scheduled to have nine of its 36 hexagonal segments installed 
computercontrolled and ready for first light or initial 
observation by august said jerry nelson of the university of 
californiaberkeley additional segments will be added as their 
polishing is completed at the rate of two per month he said 
in the meantime the edwin p hubble space telescope is 
scheduled for placement in orbit by a space shuttle crew in april 
from above the atmosphere it is expected to allow astronomers to 
see seven times as far as the most powerful earthbound telescope 
</TEXT>
