<TEXT>
retail sales rose a strong 16 percent in 
january their sharpest gain in more than a year the government 
reported tuesday analysts said the broad advance demonstrated 
enough consumer confidence to hold off any recession 
consumer spending is still alive said john silvia an 
economist with kemper financial services in chicago most 
categories showed advances that suggest to me that the consumer 
is coming back in the first quarter taking up his normal pace of 
spending 
the commerce department said sales totaled a seasonally adjusted 
1464 billion and posted their steepest increase since a 21 
percent gain in october 1988 
this positive report confirms our forecast that consumer 
spending will increase this year reversing the decline of late 
1989 commented william k macreynolds forecasting director of 
the us chamber of commerce 
december sales which originally were said to be up 02 percent 
actually fell 02 percent dragged down by a 26 percent decline in 
automobile sales tuesdays report said auto sales represent about 
20 percent of retail sales 
but car sales prompted by a renewed round of incentives that 
continued into february were up 54 percent in january the gain 
in car sales was the largest since a 66 percent advance in october 
1988 
excluding the oftenvolatile auto category retail sales still 
rose 06 percent last month 
the underlying strength is really quite remarkable said 
david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a new york 
government securities dealer you really had strength across the 
board 
it hints that consumer confidence is not fading jones 
continued as long as consumers stay positive since they count 
for twothirds of gnp the economy is likely to stay out of a 
recession 
retail sales account for about onethird of consumer spending 
which itself represents about twothirds of the gnp the nations 
output of goods and services 
the economy particularly the manufacturing and construction 
sectors slowed in the fourth quarter of 1989 squeezed by high 
interest rates as the federal reserve board kept a tight rein on 
credit to cap inflation 
durable goods bigticket items like cars expected to last more 
than three years felt the brunt of the sluggishness since many of 
these products are financed through loans 
but durable goods sales rose 39 percent in january after 
falling 21 percent in december sales of building materials were 
up 23 percent and purchases of furniture and other home 
furnishings rose 2 percent 
purchases of nondurable goods such as food and clothing 
advanced 03 percent on top of a 09 percent gain in december 
gasoline stations led the advance with a 25 percent increase but 
jones said the gain probably reflected hikes in prices not unit 
sales 
also posting gains were drug stores up 23 percent department 
stores up 22 percent and restaurants and bars up 15 percent 
grocery store sales declined 04 percent while apparel purchases 
were off 07 percent 
for the three months from november through january overall 
retail sales were up 38 percent 
