<TEXT>
a poll says most americans would rather cut 
social security taxes than use surplus funds to reduce the federal 
deficit although a poll last month phrasing the issue 
differently found otherwise 
in an abc newswashington post poll released tuesday 60 percent 
of the 1008 adults surveyed opposed using surplus social security 
funds to cut the deficit and 63 percent supported lower social 
security taxes 
however in an nbc newswall street journal poll of registered 
voters in january 53 percent favored increasing social security 
taxes in order to reduce the deficit and to keep the social 
security fund sound 
the difference most likely was caused by the phrasing each poll 
used to frame its questions question wording can dramatically 
effect poll results especially on sensitive or complex issues 
one abcpost question noted that social security taxes have been 
rising and asked which do you generally prefer higher social 
security taxes and a bigger surplus or lower social security taxes 
with the taxpayers keeping some of the surplus most preferred to 
pocket the surplus 
the nbcjournal poll by contrast said some people favored 
canceling an increase in the social security tax because the 
surplus made it unnecessary while others favored the increase 
because the surplus is needed to hold down the deficit and to keep 
the social security fund sound for the future 
just over half given that phrasing favored the increase 
sen daniel p moynihan dny has proposed rolling back 
increases in the social security tax saying it was improper to use 
the funds surplus to reduce the federal budget deficit the bush 
administration opposes his plan 
the abcpost poll conducted by telephone among a random sample 
of adults feb 14 had a fourpoint margin of error the 
nbcjournal poll done by telephone jan 1316 among 1510 
registered voters had a threepoint error margin 
margin of error means in the abcpost poll that the results 
probably are within 4 percentage points of the results if all 
adults in the nation were asked precisely the same questions error 
margin does not take into account the possible effects of question 
wording 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

