working on the moshulu for the restaurant company 
specialty restaurants which owns 68 theme restaurants around 
the nation has started soliciting sponsors among corporations and 
foundations wallace said it would cost 4 million to 6 million 
to put it under sail again 
restaurant company president david tallichet is committed to the 
idea wallace said he wants something to happen here pretty 
soon he loves the ship and so do i wallace said 
the ship originally named the kurt was built along scotlands 
clyde river in 1904 for a german company and started out carrying 
copper and nitrate from mines in chile and mexico 
the united states seized the ship when it entered world war i 
it was renamed moshulu believed to be an indian word for 
fearless the us shipping board operated it until 1921 when 
the government sold it to a company that used it to haul lumber 
in 1935 it was sold to a finnish shipper and put into the grain 
trade from australia to europe giant sailing ships raced around 
cape horn in what came to be called the great grain races of the 
1920s and 30s 
the moshulu carrying 45000 square feet of canvas won the last 
race sailing from melbourne australia to cardiff wales in 91 
days in 1939 the record was 83 days set by the bark parma in 1933 
the moshulu lost its masts during world war ii and was used as a 
storage barge 
wallace and tallichet found the hulk in finland and brought it 
to the united states the present set of masts and yards were put 
on only for show and could not carry sails wallace said 
restaurant company executive jeff mills said the tall ship could 
end up in a number of seaports either as a restaurant or a museum 
but philadelphia is not one of them our lease is up he said 
possible new locations include jersey city nj wilmington 
san francisco and san diego he said 
the fire that damaged the moshulu started when a bare light bulb 
ignited paper products in a storage area city fire officials said 
it burned the ships hold and sent smoke throughout the upper 
decks six people were injured and 200 restaurant patrons had to 
flee 
