on monday waves of grimy crude oil spilled by the tanker 
american trader rolled into bolsa chica state beach leaving on the 
beach bands of oil with a consistency of tar that were 2 inches 
thick in some spots 
about 15 miles of beaches were ordered closed to the public and 
ship traffic was barred at newport harbor anaheim bay huntington 
harbour and the san gabriel river 
meanwhile the patchedup 811foot american trader moved from a 
long beach harbor anchorage and tied up at an arco dock this 
morning to unload its remaining cargo of crude oil and to begin 
repairs of hull punctures 
an estimated 400000 gallons of oil leaked from the vessel last 
wednesday afternoon after it apparently collided twice with its own 
anchor while mooring in shallow water at an offshore oil pipeline 
divers applied temporary patches to two holes in the punctured 
hull sunday and authorities said the vessel passed watertight 
integrity tests 
the oily onslaught spared the nearby inland bolsa chica 
wetlands an ecological reserve thats home for the endangered 
california brown pelican and a stop for thousands of migratory 
birds and marine life 
there is no oil in the estuary said patrick moore of the 
state department of fish and game but birds are leaving the 
wetlands and going to the ocean and bringing the oil back to the 
estuary 
in addition to the 30footwide slick on bolsa chica state 
beach the coast guard said smaller ribbons of oil 4feetwide were 
reported near the huntington beach pier 
seventyone dead birds grebes gulls loons and pelicans 
have been found in the area and more than 200 oilsoaked birds were 
rescued and taken to a treatment center moore said 
the beach pollution was so serious that british petroleum which 
chartered the american trader put out the call for more applicants 
to add to the current work force of about 400 cleanup employees 
we are looking for people who want to volunteer to be 
employed said bp spokesman fred garibaldi 
the coast guard said onethird of the alaskan crude still 
menaced the coast staining sand as far north as long beach 
skimmers picked up 23 percent of the spill and 43 percent 
evaporated or naturally dissipated 
on the beach meanwhile politicians environmentalists and 
celebrities gathered on the sand to demand legislation at the 
federal and state levels to prevent another spill 
sen alan cranston dcalif viewed the beaches from a 
helicopter then criticized president bush for telling reporters 
monday that the spill should not sound the death knell for offshore 
oil drilling 
the president should read the environmental impact statements 
by his own department of the interior which point out that the 
more drilling platforms that you have the more tankers you will 
need said cranston 
in searching for the accidents cause the coast guard said drug 
and alcohol tests on the ships officers including capt robert 
laware were negative 
