<TEXT>
sen howard metzenbaum on tuesday criticized 
pension raiding by corporations that terminate employee 
retirement plans to gain surplus assets and turn over the pensions 
to companies holding junk bonds 
pension raids leave workers and retirees with frozen pension 
checks while their employers lugh their way to the bank with 
millions of dollars said metzenbaum an ohio democrat 
metzenbaums comments came as his senate labor subcommittee held 
a hearing on pension terminations and the potential risks from 
companies establishing replacement retirement programs with 
annuities bought from insurance companies heavily invested in 
highrisk junk bonds 
annuities are contracts that pay fixed monthly benefits to 
retirees 
surplus pension assets have become a popular target for 
corporate raiders who acquire a company and use its retirement 
programs as a source of cash 
metzenbaum focused on a proposal by the kansasbased coleman co 
to terminate employee pension funds valued at 83 million and a 
scrapped deal to buy annuities from first executive corp a 
california insurance holding company hit by financial downturns 
from turmoil in the junkbond market 
he also cited the takeover of californiabased pacific lumber 
co in 1986 by maxxam group inc which replaced an employee 
pension fund with an annuity bought from first executive and took 
control of about 50 million in surplus pension assets 
we are very worried about our pension and feel we didnt get a 
fair deal pacific lumber worker lester reynolds of fortuna 
calif told the panel 
metzenbaum said the subcommittee would consider legislation to 
impose tighter standards on pension terminations and provide 
greater protection for retirement benefits 
too often sound pension plans are wrung dry of their cash and 
replaced with annuities offering fixed benefits and no chance of 
costofliving adjustments metzenbaum said these annuities 
are backed by an underregulated insurance industry that plays fast 
and loose with everything from accounting methods to capital 
standards 
metzenbaum suggested that colemans corporate parent macandrews 
amp forbes holding inc had a potential conflict of interest in 
doing business with first executive and may have violated federal 
standards in failing to adequately safeguard the interests of 
retirees 
first executive metzenbaum said had 310 million in bonds of 
revlon inc a subsidiary of macandrews amp forbes 
coleman officials said they had acted properly 
it is my belief that the company has acted in every step 
in good faith and with full appreciation of applicable fiduciary 
obligations said coleman president larry jones 
coleman was acquired in april by macandrews amp forbes controlled 
by takeover specialist ronald o perelman wichitabased coleman is 
one of the worlds largest makers of outdoor recreation equipment 
because colemans pension plans are overfunded macandrews amp 
forbes will be able to take up to 32 million in surplus money for 
its own use by terminating the pensions and setting up an annuity 
program 
a macandrews amp forbes official said the surplus would be closer 
to 20 million after taxes and that all of the money would be 
reinvested to expand and modernize coleman finance a new employee 
retirement savings program and develop new products and markets 
our retirees will not suffer one pennys loss as a result of 
this transaction said howard gittis vice chairman of new 
yorkbased macandrews amp forbes 
coleman has scuttled its deal with first executive and officials 
told the subcommittee that it had secured the return of a 45 
million premium deposit 
coleman officials said they would proceed with their termination 
plan but would buy annuities from an insurance company carrying the 
highest rating of claimspaying ability 
