<TEXT>
president bush may use the fournation drug 
summit to revive the idea shunned in latin america of using 
us military forces to cast a radar net over colombia to track 
cocainecarrying aircraft a senior adviser said tuesday 
brent scowcroft bushs national security adviser said the idea 
was on the shelf for the moment because colombian officials 
balked last year at news reports that the united states was 
considering a naval blockade of their ports 
scowcroft said the plan probably would not win approval in the 
next several days the summit is thursday but he added that 
its an idea we think has merit he said i expect it might 
be discussed at the summit 
another administration official speaking anonymously played 
down the sensitive subject calling it not a significant agenda 
item 
bush after a predawn flight from washington on thursday will 
join the leaders of colombia bolivia and peru in the coastal 
resort of cartagena for six hours of drugfighting talks 
the summit site at a heavily guarded naval base isolated on a 
peninsula was selected to provide maximum protection in a nation 
torn by drugrelated violence 
underscoring the hazards police reported tuesday that leftist 
guerrillas had kidnapped two americans in the drug capital of 
medellin colombia to protest bushs visit they were identified 
as david kent a teacher from indianapolis and james donnelly 
employed by a company that manufactures hydraulic equipment 
colombian authorities say about 5000 security agents will be on 
hand for the presidents protection at the summit 
to bolster security two american warships have been deployed in 
the caribbean along with a colombian escort ship 
the us vessels are the uss nassau an 820foot amphibious 
assault ship which carries helicopters and a marine landing team 
and the uss sampson a 437foot destroyer armed with missiles and 
two fiveinch guns 
acknowledging risks involved in the trip scowcroft said its 
an unusual situation because there are in colombia these guerrilla 
bands terrorist bands with access to funds to purchase any 
kinds of arms and so naturally there are unusual circumstances 
however he said all the agencies involved in presidential 
security are comfortable with the arrangements 
in preparation for the summit bush called in senior advisers in 
the drug war including attorney general dick thornburgh drug 
policy director william bennett cia director william webster drug 
enforcement administration director john lawn gen colin powell 
chairman of the joint chiefs of staff trade representative carla 
hills and health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
bush also signed a new united nations compact aimed at helping 
curb international drug traffic and urged other nations to do the 
same to join us in working together to rid the world of this 
menace the menace from drugs 
the united states is the fifth nation to ratify the agreement 
tentatively approved by 76 countries the un convention against 
illegal traffic in narcotic drugs calls upon all nations to make 
illegal the production cultivation and transportation of narcotics 
and other dangerous drugs 
it also calls for tighter controls on chemicals used in drug 
production and sets up guidelines for extraditing drug offenders 
seizing drugtainted assets and curbing money laundering 
scowcroft at a briefing on the summit said the united states 
never planned a naval blockade of colombia 
instead he said the plan envisioned using offshore facilities 
to erect a radar screen that will give the colombians the ability 
to target where the loaded plans are coming from going up to north 
america and where the empty planes are coming back in and so 
forth 
scowcroft said we would be interested in improved cooperation 
in that kind of interdiction a day earlier bush said what 
id like to convince them is we can be extraordinarily helpful 
particularly to colombia in their courageous fight against 
narcotraffickers by a sophisticated interdiction effort 
scowcroft said the four leaders will sign a communique covering 
us economic assistance to the andean nations as well as aid from 
international financial institutions 
it also will call for reducing the demand for drugs in the 
united states curbing us export of chemicals such as ether used 
to manufacture cocaine from coca leaves and will deal with the 
export of us weapons to the region and with money laundering he 
said 
commenting on a dispute with colombia concerning coffee and 
cutflower trade scowcroft offered little hope that progress would 
be made on resolving such disagreements at the drug summit 
later however bennett said the subjects were open to 
discussion 
colombian president virgilio barco has complained to bush that 
the us commerce department is engaged in a trade procedure 
against colombian flower growers that could result in big tariffs 
on colombiangrown cut flowers 
scowcroft said there is nothing the administration can do about 
the matter which he described as a regulatory procedure taken 
after us flower growers protested that colombia was dumping 
flowers in this country at belowfairmarket prices 
