<TEXT>
federal job training programs fail to serve 
enough hispanics because of income and documentation barriers a 
government report said tuesday 
the national commission for employment policy an independent 
agency that reports to congress and the president said the federal 
job training partnership act needs to be amended so more hispanics 
will participate 
the report based on a 12month study called on congress to 
ease income requirements it also asked the labor department to 
urge states to loosen documentation requirements needed to get into 
job training programs 
while hispanics account for between 13 percent and 14 percent of 
those eligible for job training programs they make up only between 
10 percent and 11 percent of those who take part the report said 
the commission blamed part of the discrepancy on federal 
requirements that mandate candidates for the program be receiving 
food stamps many hispanics refuse to accept public assistance and 
therefore miss out on job training oppurtunities the report said 
because of their cultural heritage of selfsufficiency and 
attendant distaste for government assistance programs many 
hispanics would rather forego jtpa training than accept food stamp 
assistance just to qualify for the program the agency said 
the report recommended that congress change the law so that 
candidates merely be eligible for food stamps rather than 
actually accepting the assistance 
under current law receiving food stamps is one way to be 
eligible for jtpa there are also job training income cutoff 
levels which are higher in some areas than the food stamp 
qualification 
that means some working poor hispanics have income levels that 
fall between the two levels which keeps them from meeting the jtpa 
cutoff but qualifys them for food stamps 
congress needs to make the two income levels compatible so that 
hispanics falling between the two income levels who choose not to 
take food stamps can still receive job training the report said 
in addition the commission said requirements on documents such 
as birth certificates are overly restrictive in some areas such as 
miami where there are a large number of political refugees 
maybe some of us still have our birth certificate sitting in a 
drawer some place but for these people in order to get a birth 
certificate they have to get it from the very government they 
fled said carol romero the staff economist who oversaw the 
report 
the labor department should urge states to consider ways to ease 
documentation requirements the report said 
</TEXT>
