form the first government has said it will invite both south 
african president fw de klerk and recently released black leader 
nelson mandela to attend 
eckhard said 4000 troops will start pulling out immediately 
after independence and all are expected to depart by april 8 most 
of the civilian staff and the police monitors should be gone by the 
end of march or early april eckhard added 
the operation has cost more than 400 million 
shortly after un personnel began arriving last march their 
mission appeared in jeopardy when fighting broke out in april 
between swapo guerrillas and the south africanled security forces 
however the fighting was stopped after three weeks and the 
transition to independence has proceeded remarkably smoothly 
elections universally regarded as free and fair were held in 
november and seven parties captured seats in the 72member 
constituent assembly 
swapo which waged a 23year bush war against south african won 
41 seats and its longtime leader sam nujoma is expected to be 
named the first president 
there have been sporadic instances of violence but no sustained 
conflicts since the fighting in april last year 
