virgilio barco of colombia are to meet president bush in cartagena 
colombia on thursday to discuss the drugtrafficking problem 
garcia said tuesday he will request help for peruvian farmers to 
stop growing coca and produce coffee cocoa or other crops 
paz zamora told a meeting of farmers monday north of la paz the 
capital of bolivia we are not going to allow the peasants of 
bolivia to become poorer after substituting other crops for coca 
andina the peruvian government news agency quoted garcia on 
tuesday as saying peasants of the huallaga valley a major 
cocagrowing region were willing to switch crops if they were 
assured transportation for what they produced and an international 
market for it 
with those conditions in a year or two well switch over all 
the land now under coca but massive economic resources are 
needed garcia was quoted as saying 
he said peru exports about 3 billion worth of fish meal oil 
coffee silver and other products plus about 750 million to 1 
billion worth of coca and cocaine paste 
coca is enormously important to our economy the agency 
quoted him as saying 
the bolivian president paz zamora told the farmers he would 
pursue a policy of eradicating coca plantations in exchange for 
economic and social development programs 
he said barco and garcia agree with that position and he was 
confident bush also will agree 
about 1500 farmers attended the meeting monday at coroico in a 
cocaproducing area about 60 miles north of la paz 
substituting other crops for coca is the centerpiece of bolivian 
policy against drug trafficking but it has made little progress 
bolivia adopted an ambitious plan in 1988 to eradicate coca 
cultivation in seven years but as of jan 31 only 7750 acres had 
been withdrawn from coca cultivation about 5 percent of the 
officially recognized 150250 acres devoted to coca plans had 
called for the elimination of 12500 acres in 1989 alone 
part of the plan to substitute other crops for coca was the 
payment of 2000 to peasants for every hectare 25 acres of coca 
planting eliminated voluntarily peasants also demanded better 
prices for the new crops guaranteed markets and better roads and 
transportation 
on monday paz zamora said coca production allows us to keep 
our balance of payments even and for this reason we should study 
carefully the problem of substituting other crops 
in eight to 10 years when the substitution program has been 
completed farmers should have incomes at least equivalent to what 
they now make from coca he said 
