<TEXT>
nato and warsaw pact negotiators agreed tuesday on 
the basic elements of a plan to open their skies to surveillance 
overflights 
after two days of talks the 23 members of both military blocs 
took a break from highpowered meetings on german unification and 
european troopcut treaties to issue a statement accepting the 
basic principles of open skies 
the plan first proposed in the 1950s and resurrected by 
president bush last may calls for members of both alliances to let 
surveillance aircraft fly over their territory the aim is to 
enhance trust and openness in addition to monitoring compliance 
with disarmament treaties 
the communique made no mention of a warsaw pact proposal to 
share planes surveillance equipment and information the most 
controversial element still to be worked out in the plan 
the soviet union and united states had accepted the broad 
outline of the plan before the ottawa meeting 
the open skies regime is neither an arms control nor a 
verification measure per se the communique said its 
successful implementation would encourage reciprocal openness on 
the part of participating states it would strengthen confidence 
among them reduce the risk of conflict and enhance the 
predictability of military activities 
the negotiators agreed to four points 
the north atlantic treaty organization and the warsaw pact will 
implement the plan on a reciprocal and equitable basis and the 
open skies regime will ensure the maximum possible openness 
and minimum restrictions for observation flights 
each country will have an annual quota of flights the quotas 
to be decided at future negotiations 
the original plan called for larger countries to allow several 
flights a month over their territory and smaller countries to have 
at least one every three months both alliances were to have 
roughly the same number of flights 
countries will use unarmed aircraft and certain types of 
surveillance equipment to be decided during negotiations 
other countries notably the nonaligned nations of europe 
will be encouraged eventually to participate in open skies 
all nato and warsaw pact foreign ministers will meet in 
budapest hungary on may 12 to sign a final agreement said 
foreign minister gyula horn of hungary 
lowerlevel officials will continue meeting for two weeks in 
ottawa to work out the remaining issues 
although nato had rejected the soviet idea of shared aircraft 
and information both sides have expressed willingness to 
compromise 
foreign ministers from most of the 16 nato and seven warsaw pact 
contries have praised the open skies plan and said any 
remaining disputes are not likely to block a final agreeement 
us secretary of state james a baker iii opened the conference 
monday by calling the plan potentially the most ambitious measure 
to build confidence that we have ever taken 
west germanys foreign minister hansdietrich genscher said 
tuesday he was convinced this openness and cooperation will 
increasingly become the natural form of relationship in europe and 
north america 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze on monday proposed 
expanding the surveillance concept to sea and space but us 
officials quickly rejected the idea and it appeared to go no 
further 
the open skies plan is not linked formally to any other 
treaty negotiations but officials hoped early agreement could ease 
verification questions in the vienna talks on cutting conventional 
forces 
most smaller countries welcome the open skies plan because 
they lack the satellite technology to conduct surveillance on their 
own 
east bloc countries all of whose hardline communist leaders 
have lost power in the past year face critical economic conditions 
and some expressed reluctance to take on the expense of overflights 
czechoslovak foreign minister jiri dienstbier said monday that 
at a time when we are embarking on the very complicated period of 
transition to a marketbased economy we could only with difficulty 
assume excessive financial commitments 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

