<TEXT>
a new study linking natural body rhythms 
to fat and cholesterol has raised the possibility that patients 
could lose weight without special exercise or diet researchers 
said tuesday 
all you need to do is take a pill but you have to do it at 
the right time of day for the individual said albert meier 
professor of zoology at louisiana state university who initiated 
the research 
the results of the study were announced by lsu which has 
patented the procedure and licensed it to a boston diabetes clinic 
for further clinical tests and application for us food and drug 
administration approval 
the procedure in which small amounts of the drug bromocryptine 
were given at specific times was tested on 70 patients by baton 
rouge physician c william lovell and the results are being 
prepared for scientific publication the university said 
the first 33 patients in the study lost 25 percent or more of 
their fat within six weeks although they were allowed to eat 
anything and did no special exercise 
meier said people dont get fat because they eat too much or are 
lazy but because their body produces fat in a rhythmic kind of 
biology similar to that experienced by animals during migration or 
hibernation 
he said the discovery grew out of 25 years of research that 
started with whitethroated sparrows which build up body fat 
before their long migrations without eating any extra food or 
cutting down their activity 
meier who has published extensive research on birds and fish 
said he expanded his focus to include mammals when he saw the 
possibilities for humans 
other researchers in obesity called the concept interesting and 
said it would be the first bridge between human weight loss and 
studies of fat in hibernation and migration 
i hope hes right said elliot danforth jr director of the 
clinical research center at the university of vermont we need a 
breakthrough in this area 
however he said he could not assess the study without seeing 
how the researchers monitored what people ate or didnt eat 
since the nausea from bromocryptine could possibly reduce appetite 
and he said it would be tricky finding the exact time of day in 
which the pill would work 
the proof will be in the clinical effect said dr george 
bray an authority on obesity who directs the pennington biomedical 
research center in baton rouge but applying the medication in 
rhythmic doses may be enough to make it work bray said 
meier said the bromocryptine works by inhibiting secretion of 
the hormone prolactin prolactin is linked to the bodys use of 
insulin which scientists have known for years has caused fat 
production he said 
prolactins major function is to maintain receptors in the 
liver that respond to insulin the higher the level of prolactin at 
a specific time of day the more abundant the receptors and 
consequently the greater the fat production by the liver he said 
inhibiting prolactin cuts down on the number of receptors and 
thus the amount of fat produced 
bromocryptine is already fdaapproved and in weight loss is used 
in tiny doses as small as onehundredth of the normal dosage 
meier said actual weight loss per person averaged about 5 
percent 
only fat was removed no water proteins or carbohydrates 
he said 
lovell said he took the drug and lost 11 pounds in six weeks 
the only side effect was some nausea he said 
meier and lsu adjunct professor anthony cincotta now associated 
with wellman laboratory part of massachusetts general hospital and 
harvard medical school in boston reported the results of their 
study with animals in december in the journal life sciences 
in the article they said that within 10 to 15 days body fat 
was reduced 15 to 50 percent and cholesterol 15 to 40 percent in 
several animal models including pigs 
lsu has signed an agreement with ergo inc a biotechnology 
company in newport ri to market the research 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
