<TEXT>
the impact of drexel burnham lambert incs 
stunning decline reaches like an octopus beyond wall street and 
junk bonds potentially threatening many businesses that depend on 
financial markets to raise money 
the drexel bankruptcy filing could inject more sellers into the 
already depressed junk bond market which the firm dominates 
creating a confidence crisis that might spread into stocks 
highergrade corporate debt and other securities investment 
experts and business executives said tuesday 
such turmoil would affect the broader economy possibly by 
pushing interest rates and the dollar higher in opposition to 
government attempts to sustain economic growth 
drexel said its parent company was filing tuesday night for 
federal bankruptcy court protection from creditors due to problems 
stemming from the deterioration of the junk market and the impact 
on its financial holdings 
many expressed surprise at the frightening speed with which 
drexel formerly one of the most powerful investment banks hurtled 
toward collapse because of the junk bond market it was largely 
responsible for creating 
it took a long time to string together this enterprise and 
not much time at all for it to crack up said james grant author 
of a prominent financial newsletter that frequently has warned 
against the perils of junkbond debt 
others likened drexels demise to a disaster that will further 
erode the tarnished credibility of the depressed securities 
industry overall and persuade investors to shun investments that 
have no relation to junk bonds 
this could force companies that historically have relied on 
selling stocks and bonds for new capital to curtail spending plans 
lay off workers or even seek bankruptcy protection themselves 
does three mile island ring a bell with you said paul e 
berg president of berg fiduciary consultants an investment 
advisory firm in port chester ny 
when we had the explosion and problems at three mile island 
it impacted the entire utilities industry berg said referring 
to the 1979 nuclear accident youve got pretty much the same 
situation here 
drexel vaulted to prominence in the 1980s by aggressively 
peddling highinterest securities with low credit ratings as a way 
to raise money for businesses seeking to expand the securities 
became known as junk bonds because of their relatively higher risk 
of default compared with investmentgrade corporate bonds 
even before drexels latest problems a number of prominent 
deals that depended on junkbond financing had begun unraveling or 
faced serious obstacles drexel played a role in many of them 
on tuesday for example drexel client integrated resources 
inc a diversified financial services company that has been 
struggling for months sought federal bankruptcy protection 
earlier this month federal regulators seized floridas biggest 
thrift centrust bank blaming its failure partly on risky 
investments in drexel junk bonds centrust is one of integrateds 
leading creditors 
banks insurers pension funds mutual funds and other investors 
who bought junk bonds because they promised such high rates of 
interest could wind up owning nearly worthless pieces of paper 
some financial strategists said 
now the reality is beginning to sink in its coming home to 
roost that when people originally called them junk bonds thats 
exactly what they were said jack barbanel managing director of 
first global asset management an investment company in princeton 
nj 
others emphasized however that the overall number of junk 
bonds held by most investors remains only a tiny percentage of 
their portfolios the total value of assets held by pension funds 
for example is more than 25 trillion while the entire junk bond 
market once amounted to about 200 billion 
if everybody owned a piece of a junk bond it would be pretty 
small said william overgard director of investment consulting 
at buck pension fund services in new york 
drexels destiny changed dramatically after the 1987 stock 
market crash and its involvement in the ivan boesky insider trading 
scandal for which the company paid record penalties and agreed to 
unprecedented government scrutiny 
drexel has since shrunken to half its former size forced to 
sell some operations because of the agreement with the government 
still drexel has remained the preeminent marketer of junk bonds 
which have plunged in price during recent months because of rising 
concern that the debts wont be repaid 
throughout its rise and fall drexel has enjoyed strong client 
loyalty because of what supporters call the companys culture of 
hard work and dedicationmany expressed sorrow at the companys 
latest crisis 
