<TEXT>
for all thats happening in eastern europe the 
communist party remains in firm control in vietnam but a visit to 
the capital city of hanoi reveals that even here capitalism has 
obtained a toehold some stringent controls have been loosened and 
westerners are no longer looked on as ogres 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a pedicab works its way through hanois 
treelined streets dodging a jumble of motor scooters and 
bicycles delivering a japanese color tv to its new owner 
it rolls past a park dominated by a bronze statue of karl marx 
then under a large poster depicting a heroic laborer peasant 
soldier and scientist fighting to build socialism 
but elsewhere along the pedicabs route there are indications 
that fledgling capitalism is taking hold in this communist capital 
of southeast asia 
there are the dozens of privately run cafes decorated with 
colorful lights where people gather at night to chat or watch 
television over a drink that may be a 1 can of heineken beer or a 
50cent bottle of vietnamesebrand lua moi vodka 
there are shops stocked with imported tape decks and 
videocassette recorders to be snatched up by the citys nouveau 
riche 
by all accounts the vietnamese capital has become a more 
relaxed place to live as the government introduces dramatic 
marketstyle economic reforms and eases stringent political 
controls 
westerners who live in hanoi or frequently visit the city say 
they are amazed at how fast the changes have occurred they note 
the vietnamese are even becoming more colorful in their dress with 
reds and pinks replacing the drab clothing of a few years ago 
everywhere one turns western influences are clearly mingling 
with the traditional and socialist 
at a recent hanoi wedding reception for example a pop combo 
complete with sax was on stage playing an overly audible version of 
cat stevens wild world as traditional cookies and tea were 
served to about 200 guests including elderly communist officials 
staterun television also reflects the western influence 
on a recent early evening program the camera lovingly panned 
along a counter of carefully arranged lean cuts of meat the type 
of propaganda programming long found in poor marxist states but 
just a few hours later the people of hanoi tuned in to a flashy 
whitney houston music video 
socialist author nguyen dinh thi insists the party also is 
giving the countrys intellectuals more freedom he said writers 
now have the right to speak the truth even though private 
newspapers and magazines still are not allowed in this oneparty 
state 
and while a foreigner can now visit a hanoi friend without 
causing a panic over possible repercussions such visits are best 
made at night under the cover of darkness so as not to attract too 
much attention 
but for all the changes the party still rejects any challenge 
to its monopoly on power and the economy still has a long way to 
go as vietnam remains one of the worlds poorest nations 
beggars accost foreigners on hanois streets and inside 
department stores while families live in cramped apartments 
housing up to a dozen or more people 
on virtually every hanoi street dozens of young men play 
billiards on roughly hewn pool tables a sign of the serious 
unemployment 
meanwhile the colonialera infrastructure of hanoi continues to 
crumble from neglect after escaping largely unscathed from the war 
with the united states 
power outages are common and the buildings need not only a fresh 
coat of paint but substantial renovation work 
among the structures still standing is the infamous hanoi 
hilton a prison that once housed american prisoners of war but 
is now officials say home to only common criminals 
public transportation is limited with only a few buses and 
wheezing trolleys of ancient vintage on the potholed roads the 
major mode of transportation remains the bicycle 
in the countryside the rice paddies that line the main road to 
the northern port of haiphong are irrigated by hand bridges over 
major rivers are only one lane wide but handle twoway vehicle and 
rail traffic 
on a recent weekday morning scores of cars and trucks waited 
for nearly an hour as two steam locomotives belching black smoke 
laboriously chugged across one bridge 
vietnam is counting on the west to help in its modernization 
efforts particularly now that eastern europe and the soviet union 
are preoccupied with fixing their own sputtering economies 
fifteen years after the end of the vietnam war the united 
states still refuses to establish diplomatic ties with hanoi and is 
blocking vietnamese efforts to obtain assistance from international 
financial organizations 
despite the us bombing of the north during the war and the 
continued political snubs from washington the people of hanoi 
appear to hold few grudges against americans 
that spirit was exemplified by nguyen thi quy a 66yearold 
woman who lives near kham thien a hanoi street devastated by a 
1972 us bombing raid 
quy lost her 14yearold daughter in the attack every day she 
lights incense at a memorial to the victims that was erected on the 
site of a kindergarten destroyed in the bombing 
the openair memorial consists of a concrete statue of a woman 
with a dead child resting on her knee it bears the inscription 
deeply bear in mind hatred for the us aggressors 26121972 
two small bunches of flowers flank the entrance 
quy her long hair streaked gray and black began to cry when 
she recounted the loss of her daughter whom she said was making 
plans to travel abroad to study when the bombs fell 
how does she feel about americans 
i hate that american plane that killed my daughter she 
says but i dont hate the american people 
</TEXT>
