<TEXT>
when youre an aspiring musical comedy performer 
and cant get jobs because you look as if youre 12 but sing like 
alfred drake where do you go 
the precarious world of cabaret offers opportunity if not 
steady employment the latter might be a possibility now for jeff 
harnar a 30yearold babyfaced baritone who has gathered rave 
reviews since the debut last july of carried away his show 
celebrating the lyrics of betty comden and adolph green 
new york critics tossed superlatives comparing him to cabaret 
performerturnedsuperstar michael feinstein they called harnars 
innovative evening of songs done at two different nightspots 
around town one of the best of the year 
the object of their admiration is an unassuming young man who 
has struggled for more than a decade to make a name for himself in 
music it has been an effort 
harnar arrived in new york in 1979 from various points west he 
grew up in a lot of cities where his father worked for ford motor 
co it was in dearborn mich at age 5 that harnar discovered 
musicals a neighbor was doing a community theater production of 
how to succeed in business without really trying and took him 
to see it 
the whole thing the music seeing someone i knew on stage 
the sets the costumes and knowing even at that age that the show 
had a part in it i would like to do just came together harnar 
says he was hooked on theater 
harnar nurtured that ambition in high school in winnetka ill 
at a school where musicals he says were treated with respect 
when he finally got to new york in 1979 it was a different 
story musicals werent the same brash broadway musical comedy had 
given way to big british spectacle 
i was typed as a juvenile in auditions he says and then 
id sing with a baritone voice most of the roles were for tenors 
juvenile tenors i was never cast and i took that very much to 
heart 
in 1983 as his last hurrah in show biz harnar put together an 
act for a onenight run at a small club out of it came a twoweek 
booking 
but i had such a miserable time that i figured thats it i 
dont know what im going to do with this career he recalls 
what he did was put it on hold he went to work as a houseboy 
for phyllis mcguire of the mcguire sisters for three years he 
didnt sing or go to the theater i was very depressed he says 
but the job proved to be an opportunity to observe his employer 
in a similar situation 
she was launching a comeback and i was watching her go 
through the exact same things that i was going through as a 
newcomer the scope of it was a lot grander but she had to prove 
herself again to get back in the door in las vegas it inspired me 
probably even more than i realized 
it was through the course of that job that i realized that 
its not so much the talent there comes a point where your talent 
is the given its more happenstance the opportunities the 
persistence the perseverance 
by 1987 harnar was ready to try again he eventually found a 
home at eightyeights a greenwich village nightclub he was able 
to change and hone his act there finding out what was viable in 
front of an audience to support himself between engagements he 
took a job as a singing waiter at a west side restaurant 
the evening of comden and green songs was born last april but 
the songwriting team responsible for the lyrics for such shows as 
on the town bells are ringing wonderful town do re 
mi and others was not easy to persuade at first 
harnar his pianist alex rybeck and his director sara louise 
lazarus researched material from all the comden and green stage 
and film musicals but when the singer called them to get approval 
he found the team wanting to discourage the project 
harnar kept talking turning the tide when he told them he was 
thinking of singing never never land from peter pan as a 
doowop number that got a laugh out of green as well as the teams 
ok 
the title of the show carried away a song from on the 
town also is its theme in it harnar sings comden and green 
patter songs as examples of getting excessive about life and love 
for his next cabaret effort harnar and friends plan to salute a 
theatrical year he picked 1959 because thats the year he was born 
and because hes hooked on the 50s theres plenty of material 
among the shows that opened on broadway in 1959 were gypsy 
the sound of music fiorello take me along 
redhead and destry rides again as well as such interesting 
flops as juno and saratoga the list of composers includes 
richard rodgers jule styne jerry bock marc blitzstein harold 
rome and harold arlen 
when you put together a club act its entirely your favorite 
songs its exactly what i want to be singing when that gets 
received well thats the most rewarding experience i can 
imagine he says 
now my peers come up to me and say when are you going to get 
over this cabaret thing and get back to pounding the boards 
auditioning i am auditioning when auditions come along that im 
right for i go to them but the fact of the matter is im so 
happy doing what im doing 
