<TEXT>
in a significant policy shift 
the staterun television news is giving south africans a chance to 
see for themselves the dramatic political changes taking place 
across the country 
the extensive live broadcast of nelson mandelas release after 
27 years in prison feb 11 was unprecedented for a spot news 
development the south african broadcasting corp scrapped much of 
its sunday programming to show mandelas walk to freedom 
for south african television reporters it was a new experience 
they rarely had been called upon to do live commentary 
but sabcs chief political reporter clarence keyter got caught 
up in the excitement repeatedly telling viewers they were about to 
watch history in the making 
he did not have the backup that western television 
correspondents have in such situations when the mandela story 
dragged his release was 75 minutes behind schedule the studio 
provided no pretaped biographies of mandela or other short 
features that could fill the intervals thus keyter was left to 
think of new things to say when nothing was going on at one point 
the commentator described victor verster prison as probably the 
most beautiful jail in the world 
a more lively openminded approach to news coverage began when 
president fw de klerk took over from pw botha six months ago 
botha had kept a close watch on the domestic television service and 
on at least one occasion called the newsroom in midbroadcast to 
order changes 
the nightly television news shows had the trappings of 
propaganda programs carefully filtering out disturbing scenes and 
opposition accusations while emphasizing the governments line on 
every issue 
but on the night of feb 2 after de klerk legalized 60 banned 
organizations and lifted restrictions on hundreds of government 
opponents white viewers listened to televised comments from a 
string of black activists they had been taught were among south 
africas worst enemies 
in recent months viewers have seen throngs of blacks chanting 
singing with fists and banners raised marching in protests that 
would have been mentioned if at all in a sentence or two 
without pictures a year ago 
much of the change is due to carel van der merwe a journalist 
with 25 years experience in broadcasting and newspapers who 
returned to sabc as director of news last august when de klerk 
came to power van der merwes view that television journalism 
should be gripping understandable and fair has made a 
striking difference in what people now see on the evening news 
the televising of mandelas speech at a cape town rally on the 
day of his release and his news conference the following day in 
which he endorsed the organizations guerrilla actions would have 
been illegal just a few weeks ago 
us television networks carried live material on mandelas 
release and his address to the rally sabc delayed its start of 
mandelas address which began while the regularly scheduled 
evening news was on but switched live after the news and all that 
was missed were tributes at the beginning said rob stevenson 
sabcs evening news editor 
sabc is run by a board appointed by the nations president and 
by law has a monopoly on news broadcasting although two 
independent radio stations in selfgoverning black homelands can be 
heard in some cities 
during the height of political unrest in 198486 most south 
africans never saw pictures of black protests stonings arson and 
police violence that the rest of the world saw government 
officials told them night after night that the unseen violence in 
their country was caused by leaders of the african national 
congress and the communist party who were never shown and were 
quoted only selectively and rarely 
sometimes the faces of people like anglican archbishop desmond 
tutu were shown speaking while the television announcer 
paraphrased their words 
tutus first voluntary appearance on sabc was last october in a 
debate on religion in politics in which he was allowed 15 unedited 
minutes to make his points the experience encouraged tutu who had 
once refused to answer questions from sabc reporters to give more 
interviews 
hes still rather cautious about it but people in the sabc 
have told us privately there are changes and it certainly appears 
to be getting out of the tight government control said tutus 
spokesman john allen the people working there appear to be 
conservative but the journalists are exercising more discretion 
cabinet ministers who were accustomed to giving uninterrupted 
and unchallenged speeches in response to soft queries from tv 
interviewers are now being questioned on national television by 
black reporters and editors from newspapers the government once 
tried to suppress 
one of the most dramatic changes in the approach to news was 
illustrated by a transportation strike in january when more than 
30 people were killed and millions of dollars of damage done to 
governmentowned railroad equipment amid the reports of clashes 
and violence the black leader of the south african railway and 
harbor workers union was on television giving his side of the 
story 
in contrast during a mine strike in 1987 one of the costliest 
and longest in south african history the leader of the black 
miners union was never heard from until the strike ended 
for years theyve had a kind of doctrine where the official 
view always takes precedence said gus silber a television news 
analyst and freelance writer in any story about unrest or 
political controversy they always led with the official response 
the opposite way that other journalists do things 
but gavin stewart a journalism professor at rhodes university 
says the new approach does not mean the sabc is independent of 
the government it just happens that government policy is now more 
reasonable 
the sabc is only changing because the official line is 
changing agreed silber until a couple of months ago the 
official line was the anc was a terrorist organization that was 
never to be spoken to now the anc gets the same treatment as other 
organizations 
antiapartheid activists are changing their attitudes too 
answering news conference questions from sabc reporters and 
agreeing to appear on broadcasts they once dismissed as government 
propaganda 
i think people realize it makes sense to put their point of 
view to viewers of the sabc who havent heard and dont usually 
hear it said moegsien williams editor of south a newspaper the 
government suspended in 1988 williams recently was part of a panel 
questioning foreign minister pik botha on national television 
when walter sisulu and six other anc leaders celebrated their 
release from prison in october rally organizers refused the sabc 
permission to set microphones near the stage television showed 
pictures of the meeting but could not broadcast the black leaders 
words 
now sisulu appears on television and radio regularly 
van der merwe said the overwhelmingly positive viewer response 
has encouraged sabc to carry on trying to be a good news medium 
to those shocked at seeing communists and former guerrilla 
leaders speaking on their television screens van der merwe said 
they will have to accept that their own viewpoint in life is not 
the only viewpoint 
