<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert inc which rose to 
prominence by pioneering the market for highrisk junk bonds and 
using them to fuel the 1980s takeover boom now finds itself 
looking for outside help because of its deteriorating junk bond 
holdings 
the firms announcement monday that it was seeking a major 
investor or merger partner followed three days of marathon talks 
with federal regulators who worried that a collapse of drexel 
would shake public confidence in the nations financial markets 
the new york times reported 
securities industry analysts and former drexel executives echoed 
those concerns they said the firms difficulties with the 
declining junkbond market it helped create and its 1989 guilty 
plea to federal securities fraud crimes could deter potential 
investors 
at this point i think the biggest problem is the loss of 
confidence in them said chris mahoney a securities industry 
analyst with moodys investors service who would want to do 
business with them if they were a risk not to make it 
drexel announcement was another sign of decline at the firm once 
so sure of itself that it made commitments to raise hundreds of 
millions of dollars by merely saying it was highly confident in 
its abilities 
analysts said drexels capital base been reduced to a minimum 
level and that without an infusion the firm could fail to meet 
federal capital requirements 
individuals familiar with drexels internal problems said 
confidence was at an alltime low and several key executives had 
left in recent months pending litigation from its fraud woes also 
still plague the firm which has shrunk to 5300 employees from a 
peak of 10700 
financial service companies are confidence and people one 
former drexel executive said theres obviously no confidence and 
the best people have left 
led by junkbond chief michael milken who pioneered use of the 
lowgrade debt securities for multibilliondollar takeovers but 
left after his indictment last year on fraud and racketeering 
charges drexel was a symbol of the highflying takeoverdriven 
1980s 
but the departure of milken and other top performers combined 
with the big slump in the nations 210 billion junk bond market 
has hit drexel hard its large positions in corporate junk bonds 
have nosedived weakening the firms capital base 
theres no other line of business to keep them strong in order 
to make up the difference said analyst lawrence eckenfelder of 
prudentialbache securities inc 
the firms total capitalization the money it relies on to back 
its commitments and meet any losses shrank to 17 billion at the 
end of 1989 from 196 billion in 1988 leading to rumors on wall 
street that drexel was on the verge of being sold or collapsing 
drexel is the biggest player in the junk bond market so if its 
financial straits forced it to sell its holdings prices could drop 
sharply in a junk market already weakened by months of bad news 
in mondays statement drexel said its senior members had 
concluded it should seek outside assistance because unsettled 
markets particularly in the highyield area have adversely 
affected the liquidity of its parent drexel burnham lambert 
group inc 
drexel said its securities subsidiary continues to have good 
liquidity and has satisfactory excess regulatory capital 
the firm last week began to shift cash to the strapped parent 
from its securities subsidiary but the move alarmed officials at 
the federal reserve and the securities and exchange commission who 
feared it might weaken the subsidiary the times reported 
on monday drexel agreed with the government to sell assets and 
raise bank loans to keep the firm afloat the times said the fed 
requested that citibank drexels chief bank for years and morgan 
guaranty provide financing while drexel gets its house in order 
the newspaper said 
fed and sec officials remain directly involved in efforts to 
rescue drexel the newspaper said 
a drexel spokesman said the firm was acting on its own 
initiative to raise capital 
weve been in touch with the regulators all along spokesman 
steven anreder said i dont think theyre dictating what we do 
as a business entity 
federal reserve spokesman joseph coyne said he was unaware of 
any such role by the fed mary mccue a spokeswoman for the 
securities and exchange commission declined to comment 
the times also reported that the new york stock exchange had set 
up a crisis center on drexel and that exchange chairman john phelan 
had assured the exchanges board of governors that the firms 
problems were being tackled 
exchange spokeswoman sharon gamsin declined to comment on the 
report saying only that drexel burnham is currently a member in 
good standing 
jeffrey bowman a vice president at standard amp poors corp 
said the firms capital is at a minimum level 
after drexels announcement sampp downgraded its rating on 200 
million of the firms commercial paper to single b from 
a3 securities firms rely on the issuance of commercial paper 
to finance their business and the rating downgrade would force 
drexel to pay higher interest on its borrowings 
repayment of outstanding commercial paper will depend on the 
firms ability to negotiate a capital infusion or alternative 
sources of liquidity sampp said 
drexel reported a loss of 40 million on 41 billion in revenue 
for last year when it paid 650 million to settle the fraud 
charges slashed its work force by nearly one half sold its retail 
brokerage business and overhauled its internal operations under a 
civil settlement with the securities and exchange commission 
the firm had made a net profit of 523 million 951 million 
before taxes on revenue of 53 billion in 1986 
</TEXT>
