lubricant of change said alberto fresco vice president and 
country group manager of digital in europe as hungary moves 
forward with its plans to restructure its economy computers will 
play an important role 
the opening of new markets in eastern europe would be a welcome 
development for us computer makers which have been mired in a 
slump digital reported last month that its profit for the 
octoberdecember quarter fell 44 percent from a year earlier 
because of the slow us computer market 
eastern europe represents one of the few untapped markets that 
have longterm potential said terry shannon an analyst with 
international data corp a computer market researcher in 
framingham 
given the changes in the geopolitical climate this is 
laudatory on digitals part shannon said 
digital will control the hungarian venture owning 51 percent 
it has the option of acquiring 100 percent of the joint venture 
company and forming a wholly owned subsidiary in the future the 
remaining 49 percent will be split equally between kfki a research 
institute of the hungarian academy of sciences and szamalk a 
software company 
digital based in the boston suburb of maynard explored the 
possibility of doing business in eastern europe about a year ago by 
sending representatives to poland czechoslovakia and hungary 
the group found that hungary was furthest along in political and 
economic reforms and had relatively strong development in 
technology 
digitals activity in eastern europe has been severely limited 
since the soviet invasion of afghanistan in 1979 prompted tighter 
us trade restrictions with the eastern bloc 
before then however digital had significant business in 
that region said robert krause senior trade representative for 
digital 
the company now hopes restrictions will be eased by the 
coordinating committee on multilateral export controls an agency 
with representatives from most nato countries japan and australia 
that regulates what technology can be exported to eastern europe 
although digital has been unable to sell much of its equipment 
in eastern europe its machinery has been imported through illicit 
channels and computer makers there have tried to duplicate digital 
products 
fredrickson the digital spokesman said the company has not 
decided whether to service those machines 
shannon the analyst said i wouldnt recognize the existence 
of a pirated machine 
but shannon added that even if digital does not service the 
equipment it will have an advantage in marketing its products 
because the illicit base creates a familiarity with digital 
hardware and operating systems 
