<DOCNO> AP900213-0218 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the associated press asked two experts on 
eastern european economics to present their views on the prospects 
for free markets in the region marshall i goldman associate 
director of harvard universitys russian research center and soviet 
economics professor at wellesley college writes that if history is 
any guide the outlook is discouraging charles h movit senior 
economist of planecon inc in washington dc writes that despite 
enormous obstacles change is possible below is movits 
contribution 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
eastern european nations are undergoing sweeping political and 
economic change there promises to be a most difficult transition 
ahead with respect to both 
these economies have found that the growth model formulated 
under stalinist domination cannot provide satisfactory improvement 
in living standards with the gap between east and west growing and 
the price of bureaucratic mismanagement brought home more sharply 
day by day in terms of worker unrest 
what are the prospects that reforms can restore economic 
dynamism to eastern europe 
the prospects vary considerably the two major determinants of 
likely success are financial health at the outset and the extent to 
which reformers are willing to privatize and integrate with the 
rest of the world 
in some in an effort to prop up living standards in the face of 
sagging growth former regimes oversaw the buildup of an 
overwhelming debt this debt took two forms foreign loans and a 
lack of domestic investment 
in all these countries bureaucratic mismanagement and 
artificially set prices have resulted in serious imbalances and 
poor preparation for changing world market conditions to maintain 
cheap basic goods and avoid unemployment intricate subsidy systems 
have been established this has led to shoddy goods higher 
inflationary pressure and reduced incentives for people to work 
hard 
the answers for the economies of eastern europe lie in 
privatizing them to restore incentives to workers pulling down 
artificial barriers between domestic and international markets 
spurring the efficiency of domestic enterprises and allowing the 
inflow of western investment 
privatizing means both absorbing some of the financial liquidity 
of the population in the disposal of stateowned productive assets 
and relying more directly on the profit motive western investment 
would bring in resources to renovate aging capital stock inject 
more uptodate technology and improve the competitiveness of 
exports service sectors have been neglected and offer fertile 
ground for enterprises attractive in some cases to western 
investors 
even in the countries with the brightest prospects 
czechoslovakia east germany and hungary reforms must go 
radically in the direction of a dominant private enterprise sector 
this will mean a painful transition during which much economic and 
social dislocation is bound to take place 
will western investors respond to the opportunities offered in 
eastern europe there are a number of reasons to think that even 
prudent investors can find them attractive 
the region offers the lowest labor costs of all industrialized 
countries workers are relatively welleducated and highly skilled 
expected movements in exchange rates will mean moreover even more 
favorable comparison of wage rates vs potential investments 
elsewhere 
turning around east european economies will certainly require 
determination farsightedness a helping hand from western 
governments a reawakening of entrepreneurial spirit at home and a 
good deal of luck 
there is no reason to believe however that an appropriate 
combination of radically new policies could not bring new dynamism 
and a real transformation for some of these economies with a 
timeframe of about 15 years or somewhat longer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900213-0219 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when sybron corp negotiated a joint venture in budapest talks 
stalled while attorneys for the hungarian partners grappled to 
translate profit 
it was difficult to put the word profit in the contract in 
hungarian so we wrote it in german said donald rackl chief 
financial officer for the milwaukee manufacturer 
sybron weathered that and many other problems starting its first 
business in eastern europe the company expects to dance around 
bigger business potholes when its microscopeslide plant starts 
production this year 
even a veteran like pepsico inc after years of operating in 
the region has altered the way it normally does business in order 
to cope with problems alien to the west 
pepsi plants in czechoslovakia sometimes run out of bottles due 
to late shipments in the ukraine state officials snatch soft 
drink delivery trucks to haul harvested wheat said richard norton 
pepsico vice president for eastern europe 
adapting to such inconveniences is part of reality in countries 
still shaking off the dust of communist rule less easily overcome 
are structural and economic problems rapid inflation huge foreign 
debt and inconvertible currencies that make it difficult to turn 
profits into dollars 
in many respects the revolution in eastern europe remains only 
a promise several countries havent written laws on foreign 
ownership and joint ventures they lack legal systems and courts 
leaving western businesses vulnerable if for example suppliers 
dont deliver and customers dont pay 
yet for all the problems eastern europe may well represent the 
greatest commercial and financial opportunity since the rebuilding 
of western europe after world war ii the regions 136 million 
consumers crave everything from french fries to shoe polish 
telephones to computer disks 
for companies with global aspirations and patience for profits 
eastern europe is a pot of gold said chicago university 
business professor marvin zonis 
there are real possibilities out there and they ought to be 
pursued zonis said 
the commerce departments own analysts have said firms dealing 
in agriculture health care telecommunications energy tourism 
and housing may have the best chance of gaining entry and 
prospering in east european markets 
there are plenty of reasons for american companies to invest 
cheap labor is one of the biggest the average hourly manufacturing 
wage in hungary poland and yugoslavia in 1988 was 135 to 171 
said planecon inc a washington research concern specializing in 
eastern europe 
wages could even fall in dollar terms because of an expected 
decline in exchange rates 
moreover east european workers are relatively well educated and 
highly trained compared with third world counterparts low labor 
productivity may be a concern but some economists say thats 
correctable 
workers get lazy and depressed when they get stuck with guys 
who are doing a bad job of running things said edward yardeni 
chief economist at prudentialbache securities inc 
perhaps the biggest incentive for us corporations to invest in 
eastern europe is global competition us giants like general 
electric co international business machines corp and general 
motors corp are already there but so are rivals suzuki motor co 
siemens ag west germanys giant electronics company ferruzzi 
finanziara spa italys leading chemical and agribusiness company 
and british telecom others are on the way 
eugene theroux an attorney in the washington office of the 
international law firm baker amp mckenzie said its a mistake for 
american businesses to sit back and watch 
they should make at least a minimum of time effort and 
expense necessary to examine the alternatives said theroux who 
advises companies doing business in communist countries 
many companies apparently are doing just that the commerce 
department and chamber of commerce said they are receiving at least 
10 times as many inquiries as last year from american companies 
on everything from investment laws to opportunities and licensing 
commerce secretary robert a mosbacher opened an information office 
on eastern europe in january to handle all the calls 
lawyers travel agents and public relations firms are leading 
the way establishing offices and advertising for western clients 
cautious optimism has been replaced by opportunism said 
richard w edelman president of new yorkbased edelman public 
relations worldwide which has opened offices in hungary and is 
scouting elsewhere 
but american executives already experienced in eastern europe 
warn newcomers to calculate the risks many early joint ventures in 
the soviet union failed for lack of a careful business plan those 
who decide to go should be prepared to stay awhile 
this is an investment that will have longterm rewards instead 
of a shortterm immediate impact said andrew b somers jr 
general counsel for american express corp which has offices in 
several east european countries this is not something you dabble 
in 
companies in the vanguard also must be prepared to sacrifice 
time andnalds discovered 
opening its first restaurant in moscow 
the opening took mcdonalds 14 years 50 million and its own 
supply system that bypasses the deadly soviet bureacracy 
while the soviet union is considered more treacherous for 
enterprising westerners economists say eastern europe is similar 
right now if i were an american company i would think the 
prospects were very risky given the political and economic 
transition said georgetown university professor stewart brown 
congress has authorized 300 million in aid for private 
enterprise in poland and hungary as well as other assistance the 
federal exportimport bank will guarantee loans up to 200 million 
to hungary and yugoslavia 
but us companies will have to rely largely on their own 
resources to establish outposts in eastern europe 
anyone not prepared to suffer losses should not go in brown 
said 
