<DOCNO> AP900213-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
western europe is proffering aid 
eagerly to the deprived east but some european community members 
see the aspirations of their neighbors as both a benefit and danger 
to the economic blocs own integration 
political upheavals in the east bloc have raised new commercial 
opportunities at the same time some worry that the huge task of 
aiding iron curtain economies could be deemed more politically 
urgent than the communitys plans to remove the economic barriers 
dividing the dozen west european nations 
furthermore some of the communitys poorer nations such as 
portugal and greece worry that the group might direct resources to 
the east at their expense 
the community is running enormous risks because the pace 
of events has fueled the debate on european integration said 
jacques delors president of the european commission the trading 
blocs executive body 
the community must speed up the pace of european integration 
if it is to remain a focal point for others he said in a recent 
speech to the european parliament the communitys legislative body 
an ambitious integration plan by the community scheduled for 
1992 envisions a europeanwide market of 320 illion consumers 
unfettered by trade barriers the plan would create a monetary 
union with a common currency and central bank and fashion closer 
political cooperation in such areas as foreign policy 
belgium britain denmark france west germany greece 
ireland italy luxembourg the netherlands portugal and spain 
make up the community 
integration plans have not met blanket approval prime minister 
margaret thatcher for example is reluctant to make british 
monetary policy subject to a single european monetary union 
but leaders of the community also known as the common market 
have been united in the desire to help the emerging democracies in 
eastern europe convert their centrally planned economies into 
freemarket systems 
the new governments must deal with poor economic growth high 
inflation a lack of investment money and infrastructure and in 
some cases huge foreign debts 
heavily indebted poland for instance has virtually no banking 
network to support the free enterprise system needed for a 
marketdriven economy 
there are real doubts as to whether this thing can go through 
tidily even whether the transition to market economies can be 
carried through at all completely said peter ludlow director of 
the center for european policy studies a brusselsbased think tank 
the community already has directed substantial resources toward 
eastern european economic revitalization in the aftermath of the 
regions political upheaval 
aid ranging from free food to technical assistance and cash for 
improving agricultural and industrial production has been sent or 
promised to hungary and poland for example 
the community last summer was put in charge of a 24nation 
effort to devise an economic aid package for poland and hungary 
pledges have been received for a special 1 billion fund for 
poland and the west european nations recently agreed to establish 
a development bank to provide lowcost loans and other technical 
and economic assistance to eastern europe 
delors has suggested using what he called an extreme example 
that it could take 23 billion a year over the next five to 10 
years to help achieve economic reform in eastern europe 
however any call for a sizable increase in community spending 
likely would cause heated debate the communitys 1990 budget has 
been set at about 565 billion with just over half designated for 
farm programs 
an aid package for 66 poor nations in africa the caribbean and 
the pacific recently was pegged at 145 billion over five years 
willy de clercq chairman of the european parliaments external 
economic affairs committee acknowledged that poor countries might 
be concerned about future aid but he said it would be a wrong for 
the trading bloc to ignore other parts of the world 
there also is speculation that the rich nations especially west 
germany will be more inclined to channel money to the east than to 
the southern nations of spain portugal italy and greece the 
communitys weak spots 
a mark for leipzig is a mark less for lisbon goes one 
saying a reference the possible spending of west german capital in 
east germany rather than in portugal 
de clercq and others maintained the community would not neglect 
its own interests 
we dont see developments in eastern europe as a possible 
enemy of the greek economy said a greek official who asked not 
to be quoted by name after joining the community in 1981 greece 
received 62 billion over seven years to help modernize 
agricultural groups are concerned that tariff reductions and 
other special treatment for products grown by eastern farmers may 
hurt their markets 
we know we must help these countries but we must be 
careful not to create big difficulties here said andre 
herlitska secretarygeneral of the committee of professional farm 
organizations a group of community farm unions 
the european commission already has negotiated broad trade 
agreements with poland hungary and the soviet union to lift import 
limits and give their products greater access to west european 
markets 
there is a smaller arrangement with czechoslovakia likely to be 
expanded and bargaining for accords with east germany and bulgaria 
is under way the community also is taking steps to improve ties 
with romania 
trade between the community and east bloc amounted to 546 
billion in 1988 about half with the soviet union by comparison 
twoway trade with the united states that year was more than three 
times that amount 
