<TEXT>
chrysler corp said today it had a 
fourthquarter loss of 664 million including onetime 
restructuring charges of 577 million 
chrysler said the costs included idling plants in detroit and 
st louis discontinuing some car lines and reducing the 
whitecollar work force 
its called restructuring to compete chrysler chairman lee 
a iacocca said at a news conference 
more than half the fourthquarter restructuring charge of 577 
million was for supplemental unemployment benefits and retirement 
benefits connected with plant closings iacocca said the charge 
sliced 248 off pershare earnings 
chrysler said the loss was equivalent to 290 a share compared 
with fourthquarter net earnings of 433 million or 185 a share 
in 1988 sales for the quarter sagged to 79 billion compared 
with 93 billion a year earlier 
for the year chrysler reported net income of 359 million or 
155 a share on revenue of 349 billion that compares with 1988 
net income of 1 billion or 466 a share on revenue of 342 
billion in 1988 
iacocca said the results would mean no profit sharing for hourly 
workers and no bonuses for salaried employees at the nations 
thirdlargest automaker 
the earnings report came shortly after chrysler announced it had 
agreed to sell its gulfstream aerospace corporate jet manufacturing 
unit for 825 million in a cashraising move 
chrysler said it had a fourthquarter aftertax loss of 87 
million or 38 cents a share prior to the onetime restructuring 
charge 
chrysler said dec 6 it was considering selling its chrysler 
technologies corp subsidiary of which gulfstream is a part to 
raise cash and refocus on automaking 
the company has cut back excess manufacturing capacity shutting 
down its jefferson avenue assembly plant in detroit and announcing 
plans to close its st louis car assembly plant this september 
the company announced a costcutting program in october with a 
goal of cutting 1 billion from its 26billion annual budget by 
the end of this year including eliminating 2300 salaried jobs it 
since has boosted the goal to 15 billion 
iacocca called the results commendable during what he called a 
fullblown recession in the auto industry in the fourth quarter 
i am not in the least disappointed he said our cash 
position just got better and were focused 
without the cuts iacocca said we probably could have muddled 
through but we chose not to we chose to get ready for the 90s 
the countrys top two automakers general motors corp and ford 
motor co are expected to report earnings later this week gm 
reported a profit of 49 billion on revenue of 1102 billion in 
1988 and ford reported earnings of 53 billion on revenue of 
924 billion 
