<TEXT>
the parent of drexel burnham lambert inc plans 
to file for federal bankruptcy court protection today in a move 
that would cap the downfall of one of wall streets most powerful 
firms of the 1980s 
the decision on whether to seek protection from creditors under 
chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy law was expected to be approved by 
drexels board of directors drexel officials said 
drexel chief executive frederick joseph told employees on the 
firms internal communications system that the parent company and 
certain subsidiaries would file with us bankruptcy court today 
drexel burnham lambert group inc said it had defaulted on about 
100 million in loans and a lack of cash was threatening other 
defaults 
the board meeting was scheduled to start at 4 pm edt to vote 
on whether to file for bankruptcy court protection but the drexel 
official who asked not to be named said the decision already 
appeared to have been made the official said bankruptcy papers 
were expected to be filed today 
wall street traders and other sources said drexel was barely 
functioning and was liquidating its huge portfolio of government 
securities few companies were reported to be trading with the firm 
that rose to prominence through the risky junk bonds that also have 
marked its downfall 
drexel also was said to be transferring customer accounts to 
smith barney harris upham amp co which acquired drexels retail 
brokerage business last year smith barney said it was considering 
taking over the accounts but no decision had been made 
the accounts were said to be employee or employeerelated and 
include all types of securities including stocks and bonds 
drexel today also voluntarily withdrew from making markets in 
228 stocks traded over the counter through the national association 
of securities dealers 
the firm was able to maintain its duties as a specialist on the 
floor of the new york stock exchange when another firm speer 
leeds amp kellogg agreed to clear drexel trades and guarantee their 
financial obligations drexel owns the specialist firm pforzheimer 
amp co 
drexel said in a statement that a chapter 11 filing would 
exclude the brokerdealer subsidiary drexel burnham lambert inc 
and drexel burnham government securities inc 
the statement said drexel intends to engage in an orderly 
liquidation of its positions in government securities 
drexel said monday it was seeking a major investor or merger 
partner in an effort to raise additional capital drexel blamed the 
bulk of its problems on the deteriorating market for highrisk 
highyield junk bonds that it helped to create in the 1980s 
under nowindicted executive michael milken 
drexels announcement followed several days of negotiations with 
the securities and exchange commission the federal reserve board 
and the new york stock exchange over how to prevent a financial 
panic over its troubles 
the dire problems at the investment firm threaten confidence in 
the nations financial markets because of drexels preeminence in 
the 200 billion junk bond market which has been slumping since 
last fall when several companies failed to meet financing terms on 
their junk bond debt 
the firm also was hammered by its decision to plead guilty to 
six felonies and pay 650 million to the government to settle 
federal charges related to insider trading and other offenses 
drexel was forced to restructure as part of a civil settlement with 
the sec and has cut its work force to 5300 from 10700 
in mondays statement drexel said its senior members had 
concluded it should seek outside assistance because unsettled 
markets particularly in the highyield area have adversely 
affected the liquidity of its parent 
drexel said its securities subsidiary continues to have good 
liquidity and has satisfactory excess regulatory capital 
the firm last week began to shift cash to the strapped parent 
from its securities subsidiary but the move alarmed officials at 
the fed and the sec who felt it might weaken the subsidiary 
the sec stated today in washington that it had moved to protect 
the assets of the brokerage firm by barring the subsidiary from 
transferring net capital to the parent without prior specific 
approval 
inventory schedules and other detailed financial information 
submitted by drexel burnham lambert indicate at this time the 
registered brokerdealer has positive net worth and remains in 
capital compliance the sec said 
the federal reserve bank of new york issued a statement saying 
it would carefully monitor drexels decision to liquidate its 
position in government securities in consulation with the 
government drexels securities subsidiary and other market 
participants 
the bank said drexel still was designated as a primary dealer in 
government securities 
junk bond professionals said prices of those securities were 
trading slightly higher in a chaotic morning session as rumors 
swirled around wall street on whether drexel would file for 
bankruptcy protection 
dealers in treasury securities said there was concern that by 
selling off its large portfolio drexel would add supply to the 
market and depress prices pushing interest rates higher 
you want to talk about an end of an era said joan 
greenberg a senior vice president for highyield bonds at dean 
witter reynolds inc 
analysts said drexels capital base has been reduced to a 
minimum level and that without an infusion the firm could fail to 
meet federal requirements 
led by milken who pioneered use of the lowgrade debt 
securities for multibilliondollar takeovers but left after his 
indictment last year on fraud and racketeering charges drexel was 
a symbol of the highflying takeoverdriven 1980s on wall street 
drexel reported a loss of 40 million on 41 billion in revenue 
for last year when it settled the fraud charges slashed its work 
force sold its retail brokerage business and overhauled its 
internal operations under the sec civil settlement 
the firm had made a net profit of 523 million 951 million 
before taxes on revenue of 53 billion in 1986 
</TEXT>
