<TEXT>
chrysler corp on tuesday reported a 
664 million fourthquarter loss and a twothirds drop in annual 
earnings for 1989 mostly due to costs of closing plants and 
cutting jobs 
the results mean no profitsharing for hourly workers and no 
bonuses for salaried employees at the nations thirdlargest 
automaker chrysler chairman and chief executive officer lee a 
iacocca said 
but iacocca said the belttightening moves were needed to 
compete in a slow automotive market 
we looked at ourselves in the mirror back in may and we looked 
a little fat and we looked at the market for the early 1990s 
and it looked a little grim iacocca said 
much of chryslers first quarterly loss since 1982 was from a 
onetime restructuring charge of 577 million 
that covered costs of closing plants in detroit and st louis 
discontinuing some cars and paying pension and severance costs to 
trim the whitecollar work force the company said 
chrysler also said that to raise cash it had agreed to sell its 
gulfstream aerospace subsidiary for 825 million to a partnership 
of allen e paulson chairman and founder of the savannah 
gabased maker of corporate jets and the new york investment 
firm of forstmann little amp co 
weve got our capacity down our cash position just got a 
little better and were focused iacocca told a news conference 
it sounds like back to the basics said auto analyst mary 
anne sudol of fitch investors service in new york its a more 
vicious competitive environment for sure the race is to the 
lowestcost producer 
iacocca explained that the loss came during what he termed a 
fullblown recession in auto sales necessitating rebates of more 
than 1200 a car just to keep sales limping along 
i am not in the least disappointed he said 
the quarterly 664 million net loss equivalent to 290 a 
share compared with net earnings of 433 million or 185 a 
share in the fourth quarter of 1988 the company said 
chrysler said sales and revenues for the quarter sagged to 79 
billion from 93 billion a year earlier 
for the year the company reported net income of 359 million 
or 155 a share on revenues of 3492 billion down 66 percent 
from 105 billion or 466 a share on revenues of 3415 billion 
in 1988 
the onetime 577 million charge was partly offset by a 309 
million gain on the sale of mitsubishi motors corp stock the 
company said 
united auto workers president owen bieber and vice president 
stan marshall who directs the uaws chrysler department said they 
regretted earnings didnt trigger profitsharing for hourly workers 
under chryslers uaw contract they said in a statement at 
least there will be some equality of sacrifice and chrysler 
executives will have to go without bonuses as well 
chrysler has cut back excess capacity shutting down its 
jefferson avenue assembly plant in detroit and announcing plans to 
close its st louis car assembly plant this september 
the company also announced a costcutting program in october 
aimed at cutting 1 billion from its 26 billion annual budget by 
the end of this year including elimination of 2300 salaried jobs 
