<TEXT>
a man who started smoking as a child and later 
died of lung cancer should have been warned by the american tobacco 
co that cigarettes posed a health risk before the government 
required warning labels a lawyer told a jury tuesday 
but a lawyer representing the cigarette company said the victim 
george kotler was free to stop smoking and chose to continue his 
habit 
attorneys on both sides presented their opening arguments in a 
federal lawsuit against american tobacco marking one of the rare 
smokerdeath cases to reach the courtroom 
this is not an antismoking case said garry inge who 
represents kotlers widow joanne kotler this is a warning case 
this is a case of informed consent 
we admit that if george kotler knew what american tobacco 
knew they didnt need to warn him he said 
in the last 20 years only a handful of smokerdeath lawsuits 
have made it to court as cigarette companies have spent millions 
of dollars to fight accusations of liability 
the first damages judgment came in 1988 when a federal jury in 
new jersey awarded 400000 to antonio cipollone whose wife died 
of lung cancer but an appeals court last month overturned the jury 
award and ordered a new trial 
in the boston lawsuit the case centers on kotlers smoking 
habits before 1966 when government warning labels were placed on 
cigarette packs kotler who lived in cambridge was 55 when he 
died in 1986 but he started smoking around age 11 
inge told the jury that american tobacco a subsidiary of 
american brands inc in greenwich conn had information as early 
as the 1930s indicating cigarettes posed a health risk but the 
company instead insisted that cigarette smoking was not harmful he 
said 
american tobacco put profits ahead of lives he said a 
whole generation of people could have been saved 
andrew lane representing american tobacco told the jury they 
should consider not only whether kotler had adequate information 
but also whether it would have made any difference 
lane said the controversy surrounding cigarette smoking was 
reported in the press during the 1950s and the surgeon general 
issued a highly publicized report in 1964 on the dangers of smoking 
since then millions of americans have quit smoking and thus 
have reduced their risks for lung cancer lane said but the first 
time kotler showed the slightest interest in stopping smoking 
was in 1975 when he went to see a doctor because he was suffering 
from chest pains he said 
kotler stopped smoking for several weeks but when his health 
improved he resumed smoking lane said 
he smoked because he wanted to because he liked to he said 
lane also argued that in 1968 kotler switched from the pall 
mall brand an american tobacco product and started smoking 
cigarettes made by other companies 
the suit originally named two other tobacco companies philip 
morris cos inc and liggett group inc but us district judge 
walter skinner who is presiding over the case last year ruled 
that the claims were only valid before 1966 
