<TEXT>
a state judge ruled tuesday that wisconsin 
officials could collect a 5 percent sales tax from an airline for 
the drinks it sold while its jets flew over wisconsin 
dane county circuit judge james boll ordered the former republic 
airlines to pay wisconsin 90622 in overdue sales tax for drinks 
consumed on its flights over the state from 1981 to 1984 
boll rejected republics argument that a law authorizing a sales 
tax on drinks consumed in this state did not mean over this 
state 
the judge ruled the state had the right to impose its sale tax 
on flights overhead for any airline that had some definite link to 
the state such as offices based in wisconsin or incorporation 
within the state 
state officials could not be immediately reached for comment on 
whether they would seek to impose the tax on other airlines and 
seek back taxes 
republic airlines which was purchased in the mid 1980s by 
northwest airlines contended that applying the state sales tax to 
flights violated the due process clause of the us constitution 
liquor consumed in overflights was not liquor consumed 
in wisconsin the airline argued 
the airline appealed an order of the wisconsin tax appeals 
commission that it owed the tax leading to the court case 
before it was bought by northwest republic maintained offices 
in wisconsin had equipment and personnel located at airports in 
the state and flew regularly scheduled flights in and out of 
wisconsin cities 
republic said it did not keep records of whether its aircraft 
were in wisconsins air space or over another state when it sold 
drinks 
attorney frederic brouner who represented republic said he did 
not know whether northwest would appeal 
brouner called wisconsins attempt to collect the tax after the 
fact was particularly onerous 
but its a very quick clean way to pick up revenue brouner 
said how many are going to be unhappy hey only the vendor and 
corporations dont vote he said 
boll said a test for determining when taxation by a state 
violated the commerce clause of the us constitution was set forth 
in a supreme court case that held a tax would be sustained if it 
was applied to an activity with a substantial nexus with the 
taxing state was fairly apportioned did not discriminate against 
interstate commerce and fairly related to services provided by the 
state 
the tax department contends that the substantial nexus test 
is satisfied by the fact that republic maintains offices equipment 
and personnel in wisconsin and is incorporated in wisconsin boll 
said this court agrees 
</TEXT>
