<TEXT>
the 200 billion junk bond market survived a day 
of jitters tuesday after the nations biggest broker of highyield 
securities said it planned to seek refuge from creditors under 
federal bankruptcy law protection 
the markets resilience under the circumstances given its recent 
steep slide surprised some analysts who had predicted a free fall 
after drexel burnham lambert incs announcement monday that it was 
seeking a merger partner and needed money 
in announcing tuesday that it would seek chapter 11 bankruptcy 
protection drexels parent company said it had defaulted on about 
100 million in loans and a lack of cash was threatening other 
defaults 
nonetheless mutual funds that invest in the highyield 
securities those with low credit ratings or no ratings at all 
said there was no immediate rush by investors to sell 
we expected an abovenormal reaction and there were more calls 
than usual for redemptions but by and large investors have taken it 
in stride said steve norwitz spokesman for t rowe price 
associates inc in baltimore which manages a 700 million junk 
bond fund 
fidelity investments in boston which has about 15 billion 
invested in highyield securities said it had not received any 
unusual redemption requests 
the drexel situation and problems have been so well documented 
that it hasnt come as a shock said fidelity spokeswoman tracey 
gordon besides the market is not just drexel anymore 
steve radis spokesman for kemper financial services inc in 
chicago said drexels problems had not impacted the companys 14 
billion highyield fund 
drexel hasnt been supporting the secondary market for 
highyield bonds for sometime so it shouldnt impact trading of 
highyield issues radis said 
fund representatives said that despite recent losses in the junk 
bond market they had built up cash reserves lately and did not 
expect to have to sell bonds to pay off redemptions 
market observers nevertheless predicted drexels troubles could 
be damaging for market psychology at least in the short term 
drexel pioneered the junk bond market 
quite frankly their very serious problems are likely to add 
to the skepticism with which investors currently view junk bonds 
said john lonski senior economist with moodys investors service 
prices of most highyield junk bonds slid two points or 20 per 
1000 in face amount on monday but recovered tuesday as many 
investors went bargainhunting traders said 
the highrisk highyield corporate securities market has been 
under intense pressure due to a weakening economy and an enormous 
amount of corporate debt created by the merger wave of recent years 
among immediate investor worries are that drexel would default 
or have to liquidate its own huge inventory of junk bonds which 
would put further downward pressure on prices 
the market already faces a scarcity of buyers for example many 
ailing thrifts once important buyers of junk bonds have been 
forced to get out of the junk market by federal regulators 
insurance companies also have come under pressure to divest their 
junk bond holdings 
the average weekly new issue volume has plunged 86 percent from 
the average weekly volume in 1989 according to moodys the 
average net asset value of highyield mutual funds is off 6 percent 
since the start of the year lonski said 
meanwhile prospects for junkbond defaults have risen moodys 
now projects the default rate in 1990 at 10 percent up from 6 
percent in 1989 standard amp poors forecasts a similar rate 
nevertheless many junk bond analysts believe the current slump 
reflects a temporary transition phase some contend the junk bond 
market will emerge a stronger more mature entity 
because of their high yields junk bonds have remained 
attractive to many investors despite the risk average yields now 
exceed treasury yields by nearly 7 percentage points well above 
the historical average of 4 percentage points said lonski the 
average yield on a cashpaying junk bond was 149 percent as of 
monday compared with the yield on a 10year treasury note of 837 
percent 
the depth of the problems in the junk bond market has been 
overdone said one market researcher who asked for anonymity 
news of the death of the junk bond market is premature 
</TEXT>
