here is a brief rundown of developments tuesday 
in the financial crisis facing drexel burnham lambert inc 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
drexel the leading purveyor of highrisk securities known as 
junk bonds said its parent company planned to file for protection 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code which could give 
the company a reprieve from creditors while it attempts to 
stabilize and continue operating the company defaulted on 100 
million in loans tuesday after banks refused to give it more 
credit drexel also said a severe cash squeeze threatened to cause 
more defaults management told employees at drexels new york 
headquarters they would get paid thursday but the company couldnt 
guarantee anything thereafter 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
few on wall street believe drexel will survive many stock and 
bond traders refused to do business with drexel the companys 
marketmakers and brokers were openly soliciting jobs on the new 
york stock exchange floor the firm began liquidating positions in 
billions of dollars worth of goverment bonds mortgagebacked 
securities and other financial instruments negotiated to transfer 
customer accounts to smith barney harris upham amp co withdrew as 
a market maker in more than 200 overthecounter stocks and put 
entire business units up for sale the junk bond market showed 
surprising resilience to the drexel news and prices rose but 
market experts said the longterm implications of drexels demise 
could severely affect confidence in all financial markets and hurt 
the ability of companies to raise capital 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
besides drexels own workforce of about 5300 a broad range of 
investors including mutual funds and pension funds could feel the 
impact of drexels problems mostly via further price declines in 
the junkbond market drexels creditors which include a broad 
range of banks also could face risk the broader us economy also 
could feel the impact if a prolonged depression in the financial 
markets forces interest rates higher 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
drexel is a diversified investment house headquartered in new 
york its principal source of revenue has been from sales of junk 
bonds highyield debt securities of companies with credit ratings 
below investment grade that market has weakened severely in the 
past year as several major junkfinanced companies have run into 
trouble paying their debts 
drexel also has businesses in corporate finance commodity 
trading equity trading and research fixedincome securities such 
as government and mortgagebacked bonds and other areas 
once the nations fifthlargest securities firm drexel has 
shrunk severely forced to restructure after a government 
investigation into its trading activities drexel last year pleaded 
guilty to six felonies and paid 650 million to the government to 
settle criminal charges and overhauled its structure to settle 
civil securities and exchange commission charges 
drexel is a privately owned firm and as such is not required to 
disclose earnings but the firm has said it lost 40 million in 
1989 and 167 million in 1988 vs profits of 130 million in 1987 
and 523 million in 1986 
</TEXT>
